> **APJ ABDUL KALAM TECHNOLOGICAL UNIVERSITY (KTU) | 2024 SCHEME**
> - **Course:** PEERT416 - OBJECT ORIENTED PROGRAMMING USING JAVA
> - **Module:** Module 2
> - **Topic:** Object Oriented Programming in Java - Class Fundamentals

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Definition of a Class

In Java, a **class** is a user-defined prototype (or blueprint) from which objects are created. It encapsulates data (attributes/fields) and behavior (methods) into a single cohesive unit. A class is the fundamental building block of any Java application and represents a category of entities that share common properties and actions.

Formally, per the KTU 2024 Scheme syllabus, a class is a **template that defines the state and behavior common to all objects of its kind**.

### 1.2 Formal Definition of an Object

An **object** is a runtime instance of a class. It is a concrete entity that occupies memory, has an identity, possesses state (values in its fields), and exhibits behavior (through its methods). In Java, every object is created on the **heap memory** via the `new` operator.

### 1.3 The Conceptual Analogy (Blueprint vs Building)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Real-World Analogy: The Architectural Blueprint**
>
> Imagine an architect's **blueprint** for a house. The blueprint is *not* a house тАФ you cannot live inside it. It merely *describes* what every house built from it will look like: the number of rooms, door positions, materials to be used.
>
> Now consider the actual **house** built on plot #12. This house is a *physical instance* of the blueprint. It has a unique address (identity), its own paint color and furniture arrangement (state), and people perform actions inside it like cooking or sleeping (behavior).
>
> - The **blueprint** = Java **class**
> - The **house** built from it = Java **object** (instance)
> - Building many houses from one blueprint = Creating **multiple objects** from one class
> - Furniture inside the house = **instance variables** (state)

This single analogy makes the abstract concepts of *abstraction*, *instantiation*, and *state* instantly memorable for KTU viva voce.

### 1.4 Core Terminology Used Throughout Module 2

| Term | Meaning in KTU Context |
|---|---|
| **Class** | A blueprint declaring fields and methods |
| **Object** | A runtime instance of a class in heap memory |
| **Field** | A variable declared inside a class (also called instance variable) |
| **Method** | A function declared inside a class defining behavior |
| **Member** | Any field, method, or nested class declared inside a class body |
| **Constructor** | A special block used to initialize a newly created object |
| **Encapsulation** | Binding data and methods together and hiding internal state |
| **Reference Variable** | A variable that holds the memory address of an object |
| **Instance** | Another name for an object of a class |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight:** Module 2 specifically focuses on *Class fundamentals*, *Objects*, *Constructors*, *Access modifiers*, *The `this` keyword*, and *Method overloading basics*. Mastering these is a prerequisite for Module 3 (Inheritance) and Module 4 (Polymorphism).

---

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Concept Sheet

### 2.1 Anatomy of a Java Class тАФ Declaration Syntax

The general syntax for declaring a class in Java follows this structure:

```java
[access_modifier] [non_access_modifier] class ClassName [extends ParentClass] [implements Interface1, Interface2] {
    // 1. Fields (state)
    [access_modifier] [data_type] fieldName [= initialValue];

    // 2. Constructors (initialization)
    [access_modifier] ClassName([parameters]) { ... }

    // 3. Methods (behavior)
    [access_modifier] [return_type] methodName([parameters]) { ... }

    // 4. Nested classes / interfaces (advanced)
}
```

### 2.2 The Three Pillars Encapsulated by a Class

A Java class inherently embodies three core OOP principles at the *fundamental* level:

**a) State тАФ Represented by Fields**
Fields are the data members of a class. Each object of the class receives its own independent copy of these fields.

**b) Behavior тАФ Represented by Methods**
Methods are functions declared inside a class that operate on the state of an object. They define what actions the object can perform.

**c) Identity тАФ Represented by the Reference**
Each object has a unique memory address stored in a reference variable. This gives every object a distinct identity even if its state is identical to another's.

### 2.3 Step-by-Step Theory: How a Class Becomes an Object

The transformation from a class definition to a usable object happens in four logical stages:

- **Stage 1 тАФ Class Loading:** The `.class` file is loaded into JVM method area by the classloader when first referenced.
- **Stage 2 тАФ Memory Allocation:** When `new ClassName()` is executed, JVM allocates contiguous memory in the **heap** sufficient to hold all instance variables of the class.
- **Stage 3 тАФ Initialization:** The constructor of the class is invoked to initialize the fields with values (either default values or those provided as arguments).
- **Stage 4 тАФ Reference Assignment:** The memory address of the newly constructed object is returned and assigned to a reference variable (which lives on the **stack**).

### 2.4 Access Modifiers тАФ The Visibility Matrix

Java provides four access modifiers that control the visibility of class members. This is one of the **most frequently asked 3-mark questions** in KTU exams.

| Modifier | Within Class | Within Package | Outside Package (Subclass) | Outside Package (Non-Subclass) |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `private` | Yes | No | No | No |
| *default* (no modifier) | Yes | Yes | No | No |
| `protected` | Yes | Yes | Yes | No |
| `public` | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Use `\vert` notation instead of literal pipe characters when expressing *visible* vs *not visible*. For example: $\text{private} \rightarrow \text{within class} \mid \text{denied elsewhere}$

### 2.5 The `this` Keyword тАФ Why It Exists

The `this` keyword is a reference variable that refers to the **current invoking object**. It serves three primary purposes:

- **Disambiguation:** Differentiates instance variables from parameters/local variables when they share the same name.
- **Constructor Chaining:** Invokes another constructor of the same class using `this([args])`.
- **Method Passing:** Passes the current object as a parameter to another method using `this` as an argument.

### 2.6 Constructors тАФ The Object Initializer

A constructor is a special method-like block used to initialize an object. Its defining properties:

- Has the **same name** as the class.
- Has **no return type** (not even `void`).
- Is **automatically invoked** when an object is created via `new`.
- If no constructor is defined, the compiler provides a **default no-argument constructor**.

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Utility:** In industrial Java (used in banking, e-commerce, embedded systems), classes encapsulate business entities. For example, a `BankAccount` class encapsulates fields like `accountNumber`, `balance`, and methods like `deposit()`, `withdraw()`. Encapsulation ensures that `balance` cannot be directly modified from outside тАФ protecting the integrity of financial data. This same principle applies to IoT systems, Android apps, and enterprise software.

---

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
## 3. Step-by-Step Code Analysis & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Worked Example: A Complete Student Class

Below is a fully commented, KTU-exam-style program demonstrating every class-fundamental concept in Module 2.

```java
// File: Student.java
public class Student {
    // ---- STEP A: PRIVATE FIELDS (State) ----
    private String name;
    private int rollNumber;
    private double cgpa;

    // ---- STEP B: DEFAULT CONSTRUCTOR ----
    public Student() {
        this.name = "Not Assigned";
        this.rollNumber = 0;
        this.cgpa = 0.0;
        System.out.println("Default constructor invoked.");
    }

    // ---- STEP C: PARAMETERIZED CONSTRUCTOR ----
    public Student(String name, int rollNumber, double cgpa) {
        this.name = name;          // 'this.name' = instance variable
        this.rollNumber = rollNumber;
        this.cgpa = cgpa;
        System.out.println("Parameterized constructor invoked.");
    }

    // ---- STEP D: COPY CONSTRUCTOR (advanced) ----
    public Student(Student other) {
        this.name = other.name;
        this.rollNumber = other.rollNumber;
        this.cgpa = other.cgpa;
    }

    // ---- STEP E: METHODS (Behavior) ----
    public void displayDetails() {
        System.out.println("Name      : " + this.name);
        System.out.println("Roll No   : " + this.rollNumber);
        System.out.println("CGPA      : " + this.cgpa);
    }

    public void updateCGPA(double newCGPA) {
        if (newCGPA >= 0.0 && newCGPA <= 10.0) {
            this.cgpa = newCGPA;
        } else {
            System.out.println("Invalid CGPA. Update rejected.");
        }
    }

    // ---- STEP F: GETTER METHOD ----
    public String getName() {
        return this.name;
    }

    // ---- STEP G: STATIC MEMBER (Class-level) ----
    private static int studentCount = 0;

    public static int getStudentCount() {
        return studentCount;
    }
}
```

```java
// File: Main.java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Creating objects using constructors
        Student s1 = new Student();
        Student s2 = new Student("Ananya", 45, 9.2);
        Student s3 = new Student(s2); // Copy constructor

        // Calling methods
        s1.displayDetails();
        s2.displayDetails();
        s2.updateCGPA(9.5);
        s3.displayDetails();

        System.out.println("Student Name: " + s2.getName());
    }
}
```

### 3.2 Exhaustive Line-by-Line Explanation

- **Line `private String name;`**: Declares a private instance variable. Private means it cannot be accessed directly outside the class тАФ this enforces **encapsulation**.
- **Line `public Student() { ... }`**: A no-argument constructor. If absent, Java inserts a default one. Used to initialize objects with default values.
- **Line `this.name = "Not Assigned";`**: The `this` keyword disambiguates the field `name` from any local variable of the same name.
- **Line `public Student(String name, int rollNumber, double cgpa)`**: Parameterized constructor. Accepts values at object creation time.
- **Line `this.name = name;`**: Left side is the *instance variable* of the current object. Right side is the *local parameter* of the constructor.
- **Line `public Student(Student other)`**: Copy constructor тАФ creates a new object as a copy of an existing one. Not provided by Java automatically.
- **Line `if (newCGPA >= 0.0 && newCGPA <= 10.0)`**: Validation logic тАФ demonstrates that encapsulation protects data integrity.
- **Line `private static int studentCount`**: A class-level (static) variable shared across all `Student` objects. Belongs to the class, not any instance.
- **Line `Student s2 = new Student("Ananya", 45, 9.2);`**: `new` allocates heap memory, constructor initializes it, reference `s2` (on stack) points to that heap address.

### 3.3 Analytical Matrix: Stack vs Heap Memory Behavior

The following mathematical model describes the memory layout when an object is created.

$$
\text{Total Object Memory} = \text{Object Header} + \sum_{i=1}^{n} \text{size}(field_i) + \text{Padding}
$$

Where:

- $\text{Object Header}$ typically occupies **12 bytes** on a 64-bit JVM (containing class pointer, hash code, lock info).
- $\text{size}(field_i)$ is the JVM-allocated size of each field.
- $\text{Padding}$ aligns the total size to an 8-byte boundary.

For our `Student` class, the memory footprint is approximately:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Memory}_{\text{Student}} &= 12 \text{ (header)} + 4 \text{ (int rollNumber)} \\
&\quad + 8 \text{ (double cgpa)} + 4 \text{ (String reference)} \\
&= 28 \text{ bytes (before padding)}
\end{aligned}
$$

After alignment:

$$
\text{Memory}_{\text{Student aligned}} = 32 \text{ bytes}
$$

### 3.4 Object Lifecycle State Diagram (Conceptual Model)

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Class Loaded} &\xrightarrow{\text{new Keyword}} \text{Memory Allocated in Heap} \\
&\xrightarrow{\text{Constructor Called}} \text{Object Initialized} \\
&\xrightarrow{\text{Reference Assigned}} \text{Object in Use (Live State)} \\
&\xrightarrow{\text{All References Nullified}} \text{Unreachable (Eligible for GC)} \\
&\xrightarrow{\text{Garbage Collector Runs}} \text{Memory Reclaimed}
\end{aligned}
$$

> [!NOTE]
> **Why `this` Cannot Be Used in `static` Context:** In a static method, there is no "current object" because static methods belong to the class, not to any instance. Therefore, `this` would have no meaningful value and the compiler rejects it with error: *"non-static variable this cannot be referenced from a static context"*.

### 3.5 Constructor Overloading vs Method Overloading

Both use Java's *compile-time polymorphism* (static binding). The compiler distinguishes between overloaded constructors based on the **number, type, and order of parameters** тАФ not on the return type.

$$
\text{Method Signature} = \text{Method Name} + \text{Parameter List}
$$

Two methods/constructors with the same name but different parameter lists are considered distinct signatures.

---

<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

