## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### Part A тАФ Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

**Q1. Differentiate between a class and an object with a suitable example.** `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`

**Model Answer:**

| Aspect | Class | Object |
|---|---|---|
| Definition | A blueprint or template | A runtime instance of a class |
| Memory | No memory allocated at definition | Memory allocated on heap when created |
| Declaration | Declared once using `class` keyword | Created using `new` keyword (multiple allowed) |
| Existence | Logical existence | Physical/runtime existence |
| Example | `class Car { ... }` | `Car myCar = new Car();` |

A class `Car` may declare fields like `color`, `speed` and a method `accelerate()`. The object `myCar` is a specific car тАФ say a red Swift with speed 60 km/h тАФ that exists in memory at runtime.

*Word count target: 80тАУ100 words for full 3 marks.*

---

**Q2. What is encapsulation? How is it achieved in Java?** `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**Model Answer:**

**Encapsulation** is the OOP principle of binding data (fields) and the methods that operate on that data into a single unit (class), and restricting direct external access to some of the object's components.

It is achieved in Java by:

1. Declaring fields as **`private`** тАФ so they cannot be accessed directly from outside the class.
2. Providing **`public` getter and setter methods** тАФ to control how fields are read and modified.
3. Adding **validation logic** inside setters тАФ to maintain data integrity.

Example:

```java
public class BankAccount {
    private double balance;  // hidden data
    public double getBalance() { return balance; }  // controlled access
    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) balance += amount;  // validation
    }
}
```

---

### Part B тАФ Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each тАФ Module Internal Choice)

---

### **Question A (14 Marks)**

**(a)** Explain the structure of a Java class with a suitable example program. Discuss fields, constructors, and methods in detail. **(7 marks)** `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`

**Model Solution:**

A Java class is declared using the `class` keyword followed by a class name and a body enclosed in curly braces. The structure includes:

**1. Fields (Instance Variables):** These represent the **state** of an object. Each object gets its own copy. Example: `String name; int roll;`

**2. Constructors:** Special blocks invoked automatically when an object is created using `new`. Used to initialize fields. They share the class name and have no return type.

**3. Methods:** Functions declared inside the class that represent **behavior**. They operate on the state of the object.

Example program:

```java
class Rectangle {
    private double length;
    private double width;

    // Default constructor
    public Rectangle() {
        this.length = 1.0;
        this.width = 1.0;
    }

    // Parameterized constructor
    public Rectangle(double length, double width) {
        this.length = length;
        this.width = width;
    }

    // Method to compute area
    public double area() {
        return this.length * this.width;
    }

    // Method to display details
    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Length: " + length + ", Width: " + width);
        System.out.println("Area: " + area());
    }
}

public class TestRectangle {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Rectangle r1 = new Rectangle();
        Rectangle r2 = new Rectangle(5.0, 3.0);
        r1.display();
        r2.display();
    }
}
```

In this program, `Rectangle` is the class. The fields `length` and `width` represent state. The constructors initialize objects. The `area()` and `display()` methods represent behavior.

---

**(b)** Explain the use of the `this` keyword in Java with examples. List at least three different uses. **(7 marks)** `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**Model Solution:**

The `this` keyword is a reference variable in Java that refers to the **current object** тАФ the instance whose method or constructor is being executed.

**Use 1: Disambiguating instance variables from parameters**

When constructor parameters have the same name as fields, `this` resolves the ambiguity.

```java
class Employee {
    private String name;
    private int id;
    public Employee(String name, int id) {
        this.name = name;   // this.name = field, name = parameter
        this.id = id;
    }
}
```

**Use 2: Constructor chaining using `this()`**

A constructor can invoke another constructor of the same class using `this([arguments])`. This reduces code duplication.

```java
class Box {
    int length, breadth, height;
    Box() { this(1, 1, 1); }              // chain to 3-arg constructor
    Box(int l, int b) { this(l, b, 1); }  // chain to 3-arg constructor
    Box(int l, int b, int h) {            // master constructor
        this.length = l;
        this.breadth = b;
        this.height = h;
    }
}
```

**Use 3: Passing the current object as an argument**

```java
class Helper {
    void show(Employee e) { System.out.println(e.getName()); }
}
class Employee {
    private String name = "Ravi";
    public void passSelf() {
        new Helper().show(this);  // passes the current Employee object
    }
    public String getName() { return name; }
}
```

**Use 4: Returning the current object from a method**

```java
public Employee setName(String name) {
    this.name = name;
    return this;   // enables method chaining like obj.setName("A").setId(101);
}
```

`this` cannot be used inside static methods because no current instance exists in a static context.

---

### **Question B (14 Marks) тАФ Alternative Choice**

**(a)** Explain the four access modifiers in Java with a comparative table. Give an example program demonstrating their scope. **(7 marks)** `[KTU University Exam - May 2023]`

**Model Solution:**

Java provides four access modifiers that control the visibility of classes, methods, and fields:

1. **`private`** тАФ Accessible only within the same class.
2. **Default (package-private)** тАФ Accessible within the same package. Used when no modifier is specified.
3. **`protected`** тАФ Accessible within the same package **and** by subclasses in other packages.
4. **`public`** тАФ Accessible from everywhere.

**Comparative Table:**

| Modifier | Same Class | Same Package | Subclass (Other Package) | Other Package |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `private` | Yes | No | No | No |
| default | Yes | Yes | No | No |
| `protected` | Yes | Yes | Yes | No |
| `public` | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes |

**Example Program:**

```java
package university.dept;

public class Student {
    private String aadhar;     // accessible only inside Student
    String section;            // default тАФ accessible in university.dept
    protected int semester;    // accessible in dept + subclasses elsewhere
    public String name;        // accessible everywhere

    public void show() {
        System.out.println(aadhar);     // OK тАФ same class
        System.out.println(section);    // OK тАФ same class
        System.out.println(semester);   // OK тАФ same class
        System.out.println(name);       // OK тАФ same class
    }
}
```

```java
package university.dept;  // same package
class TestSamePackage {
    void test() {
        Student s = new Student();
        // s.aadhar тАФ ERROR: private
        System.out.println(s.section);    // OK: default
        System.out.println(s.semester);   // OK: protected
        System.out.println(s.name);       // OK: public
    }
}
```

```java
package university.exam;  // different package, subclass
class ExamCell extends Student {
    void test() {
        Student s = new Student();
        // s.aadhar тАФ ERROR
        // s.section тАФ ERROR: default not visible
        System.out.println(s.semester);   // OK: protected via inheritance
        System.out.println(s.name);       // OK: public
    }
}
```

---

**(b)** What are constructors? Explain default, parameterized, and copy constructors with examples. How does constructor overloading work? **(7 marks)** `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2022]`

**Model Solution:**

A **constructor** is a special member of a class used to initialize an object at the time of its creation. Its defining features:

- Same name as the class.
- No return type (not even `void`).
- Invoked automatically by the `new` operator.
- If no constructor is defined, Java provides a default no-argument constructor.

**1. Default Constructor**

Takes no arguments. Initializes fields to default values.

```java
class Course {
    String courseName;
    int credits;
    public Course() {
        this.courseName = "Undeclared";
        this.credits = 0;
    }
}
```

**2. Parameterized Constructor**

Accepts parameters to initialize fields with user-provided values at creation time.

```java
public Course(String courseName, int credits) {
    this.courseName = courseName;
    this.credits = credits;
}
```

**3. Copy Constructor**

Accepts an object of the same class and copies its field values into the new object. Java does not provide this automatically тАФ the programmer must define it explicitly.

```java
public Course(Course other) {
    this.courseName = other.courseName;
    this.credits = other.credits;
}
```

**Constructor Overloading:**

A class may have multiple constructors, each with a different parameter list (different number, type, or order of parameters). The compiler chooses the appropriate one based on the arguments passed to `new`.

```java
class Course {
    String name; int credits;
    Course() { this.name = "NA"; this.credits = 0; }
    Course(String n) { this.name = n; this.credits = 3; }
    Course(String n, int c) { this.name = n; this.credits = c; }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Course c1 = new Course();             // calls 1st
        Course c2 = new Course("Java");       // calls 2nd
        Course c3 = new Course("OOP", 4);     // calls 3rd
    }
}
```

Constructor overloading promotes flexibility, allowing objects to be initialized in multiple ways depending on context.

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning тАФ Common Mark Deductions**
>
> 1. **Forgetting to mention the difference between *reference* and *object*.** Many students write *"s1 is an object"*. The correct phrasing is: **"`s1` is a reference variable that points to an object on the heap."** Marks are lost for this in Part A.
>
> 2. **Confusing `private` with `protected`.** Private is **never** accessible outside the class тАФ not even to subclasses. Protected *is* accessible to subclasses in other packages.
>
> 3. **Writing constructors with a return type.** `public void Student()` is **not** a constructor тАФ it is a method. Constructors must have no return type at all.
>
> 4. **Assuming Java provides a default copy constructor like C++.** Java does not. You must define one manually.
>
> 5. **Using `this` inside a `static` context.** This is a compile-time error. Always state why: *"no current instance exists in a static method."*
>
> 6. **In Part B questions, skipping the table comparison.** KTU examiners specifically reward tabular comparison answers with bonus clarity marks.

---

### Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!NOTE]
> **Rapid-Revision Checklist for Module 2 тАФ Class Fundamentals**
>
> - A **class** is a blueprint; an **object** is an instance created from it using `new`.
> - A class has **fields** (state), **methods** (behavior), and **constructors** (initialization logic).
> - Every Java file with `public class X` must be named `X.java`. This is **mandatory**.
> - `private` members are accessible **only within the same class** тАФ the strictest visibility.
> - Default (no-modifier) visibility = **package-private** = same package only.
> - `protected` = package + subclasses (even in other packages).
> - `public` = visible from anywhere a class is accessible.
> - Constructors share the class name, have no return type, and are invoked by `new`.
> - The **default constructor** disappears the moment you define any explicit constructor.
> - Constructor overloading = multiple constructors with different parameter lists.
> - Copy constructors must be defined manually in Java (unlike C++).
> - The `this` keyword refers to the **current object** тАФ used for disambiguation, chaining, and passing.
> - `this()` calls another constructor тАФ must be the **first statement** in the calling constructor.
> - Static variables belong to the **class**; instance variables belong to **each object**.
> - `this` cannot be used in `static` methods or `static` blocks.
> - Encapsulation = `private` data + `public` controlled access + validation in setters.
> - Objects are created on the **heap**; reference variables live on the **stack**.
> - When all references to an object are lost, it becomes **eligible for garbage collection** (not immediately destroyed).
> - Java is **pass-by-value** тАФ but for object references, the *value* being passed is the address (so object contents can be modified, but the original reference cannot be reassigned by the called method).
> - A class can have any number of methods, but a `public` class can exist at most **one per file**.
> - Method signature = method name + parameter list. Return type is **not** part of the signature.
> - Naming convention: class names use **PascalCase**; fields/methods use **camelCase**.

