# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference

## 2.1 Returning Objects тАФ Operational Logic

When a method declares a class type as its return type, the following sequence occurs:

1. The method body creates (or obtains) an object on the **heap**.
2. A **reference variable** holding the heap address is prepared.
3. The `return` statement transfers that reference back to the **caller's stack frame**.
4. The caller stores the reference in a variable of the same class type.
5. Both the original variable inside the method and the caller's variable now point to the **same object** тАФ changes are mutually visible.

### Key Properties

- Returning an object **does not** copy the object; only the **reference** is copied.
- A method may return `null`, indicating "no object".
- A method may return `this` (the current object), enabling **method chaining**.

---

## 2.2 Static Members тАФ Operational Logic

### 2.2.1 Static Variables

- Declared with the `static` keyword inside a class but **outside** any method.
- **Single shared copy** across all objects.
- Stored in the **Method Area (Class Area)** of the JVM memory, *not* in individual object heaps.
- Initialized when the class is loaded by the ClassLoader.
- Default values are the same as instance variables (`0`, `0.0`, `false`, `null`).

### 2.2.2 Static Methods

- Declared with the `static` keyword.
- Invoked using the **class name** (preferred) тАФ `ClassName.methodName()` тАФ or via an object reference (discouraged).
- **Restrictions**:
  * Cannot use `this` or `super` keywords.
  * Cannot directly access **non-static (instance) members** тАФ must invoke them via an object reference.
  * Can call other static methods and access static variables directly.
- Used for **utility/helper** logic (e.g., `Math.sqrt()`, `Integer.parseInt()`).

### 2.2.3 Static Blocks

- Executed **once**, when the class is first loaded into memory.
- Used to initialize static variables or load native libraries.
- Multiple static blocks execute in the **order they appear** in the source code.

---

## 2.3 KTU High-Yield Reference Table

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The table below summarizes every rule tested in KTU examinations. Memorize it.

### Comparison: Static vs Instance

| Feature | Static Member | Instance Member |
|---|---|---|
| Keyword | `static` | No `static` keyword |
| Belongs to | The **class** | Each **object** (instance) |
| Memory location | **Method Area** of JVM | **Heap** (per object) |
| Number of copies | **One** per class | **One per object** |
| Access via | `ClassName.member` (preferred) | `objectReference.member` |
| `this` keyword allowed? | No | Yes |
| Can access instance members? | Only through an object | Yes, directly |
| Lifetime | Until class is unloaded | Until object is GC'd |
| Loaded at | **Class loading time** | **Object creation time** |
| Example | `Math.PI`, `System.out` | `name`, `rollNo` of a Student |

### Rules of `return` with Objects

| Scenario | Return Type Declaration | What is Returned |
|---|---|---|
| Return object of same class | `MyClass methodName()` | Reference to a `MyClass` object |
| Return object of subclass | `ParentClass methodName()` | Reference to `Parent` (or child) тАФ **upcasting** |
| Return `this` | `MyClass methodName()` | Reference to current invoking object |
| Return `null` | `MyClass methodName()` | Indicates "no object" |
| Return new object | `MyClass methodName()` | Reference to freshly allocated object |
