## 3.3 Walkthrough 3 тАФ Static Members (Memory & Lifetime Analysis)

```java
class Employee {
    int id;                       // instance variable
    static int companyCode = 1001; // static variable (shared)
    static String companyName = "KTU Tech Pvt. Ltd.";

    Employee(int id) {
        this.id = id;
    }

    static void changeCompanyName(String newName) {
        companyName = newName;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("ID: " + id + ", Code: " + companyCode + ", Company: " + companyName);
    }
}

class TestEmployee {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee e1 = new Employee(1);
        Employee e2 = new Employee(2);

        System.out.println("Before change:");
        e1.display();
        e2.display();

        Employee.changeCompanyName("New KTU Industries");

        System.out.println("\nAfter change:");
        e1.display();
        e2.display();
    }
}
```

### Output

```
Before change:
ID: 1, Code: 1001, Company: KTU Tech Pvt. Ltd.
ID: 2, Code: 1001, Company: KTU Tech Pvt. Ltd.

After change:
ID: 1, Code: 1001, Company: New KTU Industries
ID: 2, Code: 1001, Company: New KTU Industries
```

### Memory Layout

| Memory Region | Contents |
|---|---|
| **Method Area (Class Area)** | `companyCode = 1001`, `companyName = "KTU Tech Pvt. Ltd."`, method bytecode |
| **Heap тАФ Object e1** | `id = 1` (only) |
| **Heap тАФ Object e2** | `id = 2` (only) |
| **Stack тАФ main()** | references `e1` and `e2` |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Notice that the static variable `companyCode` is **NOT** duplicated inside `e1` or `e2`. Both objects **read** the same copy from the Method Area. After calling the static method, the value is updated **once**, and both objects see the new value.

