## Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1
**[KTU University Exam тАУ Model Question, Module 2]**

**What is a static variable? How does it differ from an instance variable? (3 Marks)**

#### Model Answer
A **static variable** is declared using the `static` keyword inside a class but outside any method. It belongs to the **class itself**, not to any individual object, so only **one copy** exists and is shared by all objects of the class. An **instance variable**, in contrast, is declared without the `static` keyword; **each object** gets its own independent copy, allocated in the heap when the object is created. Static variables are stored in the **Method Area** of the JVM and live for the entire duration the class is loaded, while instance variables live as long as the object that owns them is reachable.

---

### Question 2
**[KTU University Exam тАУ Model Question, Module 2]**

**Explain how a method can return an object in Java with a small example. (3 Marks)**

#### Model Answer
A method can return an object simply by declaring the return type as a **class name**. The method may either create a new object using `new` or return a reference to an existing object, often using `return this` or `return objRef;`. What is actually returned is the **reference (address)** to the object on the heap, not a copy of the object itself.

```java
class Number {
    int value;
    Number(int v) { value = v; }
    Number negate() { return new Number(-value); }
}
```

Here, `negate()` returns a brand new `Number` object whose `value` is the negation of the calling object's `value`.

