**(b) Write a Java program that demonstrates returning objects from methods. Use the concept of a factory method that returns an object based on a parameter. (7 Marks)**

#### Model Solution

```java
class Shape {
    void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing a generic shape"); }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
    @Override
    void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing a Circle"); }
}

class Square extends Shape {
    @Override
    void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing a Square"); }
}

// Factory class that returns Shape objects
class ShapeFactory {
    static Shape getShape(String type) {
        if (type == null) return null;
        if (type.equalsIgnoreCase("circle")) return new Circle();
        if (type.equalsIgnoreCase("square")) return new Square();
        return new Shape();
    }
}

class TestFactory {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Shape s1 = ShapeFactory.getShape("circle");
        Shape s2 = ShapeFactory.getShape("square");

        s1.draw();
        s2.draw();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Drawing a Circle
Drawing a Square
```

**Explanation:**

- The static method `getShape(String type)` has a return type of `Shape` (the parent class), so it can return **any subclass object** тАФ this is **upcasting**.
- The method constructs the appropriate subclass object based on the input parameter and returns its reference.
- The caller, unaware of the actual subclass, invokes `draw()` тАФ **runtime polymorphism** dispatches the call to the correct overridden method.
- Note: the factory method itself is `static`, illustrating how static methods can return objects of any class.

