# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition Block**
> **Inner Class:** An *Inner Class* (also called a *Nested Class*) in Java is a class that is declared as a member of another class or within a block of code. It logically groups helper classes that are only used in one place, increases encapsulation, and can directly access the private members of its enclosing (outer) class.
>
> **Super Class (Inheritance):** A *Super Class* (also called a *Parent Class* or *Base Class*) is the class from which features (fields) and behaviours (methods) are inherited. The class that inherits these features is called the *Sub Class* (Child Class / Derived Class). The keyword used is `extends`, and `super` is the reference variable used to refer to the immediate parent class object.

---

## 1.1 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

### Analogy for Inner Classes тАФ "The Wallet Inside Your Pocket"
Think of your **pocket** as a class `Pocket` and your **wallet** as another class `Wallet` that lives *inside* the pocket. The wallet:
- Is **not useful** without the pocket (it only makes sense within the context of the pocket),
- Has **direct, private access** to things inside the pocket (coins, cards),
- Is **encapsulated** тАФ outside code cannot directly instantiate a wallet without going through the pocket logic.

In Java, an *Inner Class* works exactly like this тАФ it is a helper class that lives inside another class, enjoys privileged access to the outer class's private members, and cannot exist meaningfully on its own.

### Analogy for Inheritance / Super Class тАФ "The Family Tree"
Consider a real-world **family tree**:
- The **Father** (Super Class) has properties like `surname`, `eyeColor`, and behaviours like `walk()`, `speak()`.
- The **Son** (Sub Class) inherits all these automatically, but can **add** new properties (e.g., `bike`) or **override** a behaviour (e.g., his own way of `speak()`).
- The Son can still refer to his father's original behaviour using a special handle тАФ the `super` keyword тАФ just like calling out *"Dad, how do you do this?"* before doing it his own way.

In Java, `super` is that special handle, and the **super class** is the parent whose members get inherited.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU High-Yield Highlight:** In Java, **only single inheritance** is supported for classes (a class can extend only ONE super class), but a class can implement **multiple interfaces**. This is a common 3-mark question.

