## 1.3 Formal KTU 2024 Taxonomy of Inner Classes

Java defines **four** types of inner (nested) classes. Memorise the table below тАФ it is worth at least one direct question per exam cycle.

| Type | Where Declared | Can Access Outer Private Members? | Needs Outer Instance? |
|------|----------------|----------------------------------|----------------------|
| **Member Inner Class** | Inside another class, at member level | Yes | Yes |
| **Static Nested Class** | Inside another class, with `static` modifier | No (only static members) | No |
| **Local Inner Class** | Inside a method / block / constructor | Yes | Yes (effectively) |
| **Anonymous Inner Class** | Inside an expression, no name | Yes (if non-static context) | Yes (if non-static context) |

> [!TIP]
> **Exam Trick:** A *static nested class* is technically **not** called an "inner class" in the strict Java Language Specification тАФ it is a "nested class". However, KTU textbooks and exam papers use the term "inner class" loosely to cover all four. Remember this distinction for viva questions.

---

## 1.4 Formal Definition of Super Class in Inheritance

**Inheritance** is the OOP mechanism in Java by which one class (the *sub class*) is allowed to inherit the features (fields) and behaviours (methods) of another class (the *super class*), using the `extends` keyword.

```java
class SuperClass {
    // parent members
}

class SubClass extends SuperClass {
    // inherits all accessible members of SuperClass
    // can add new members
    // can override methods
}
```

The `super` keyword in Java has **three primary uses** тАФ these are the most-asked theoretical points in KTU exams:

1. **`super.memberName`** тАФ to refer to the **super class's field or method** when it has been hidden/overridden by the sub class.
2. **`super(arguments)`** тАФ to explicitly invoke a **super class constructor** from the sub class constructor.
3. **`super.methodName(arguments)`** тАФ to explicitly invoke an **overridden super class method**.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rule:** A call to `super()` **must be the first statement** in a sub class constructor. If not written explicitly, the compiler **automatically inserts a no-argument `super()` call** as the first line of every constructor.
