# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 Inner Classes тАФ Deep Theoretical Breakdown

### 2.1.1 Why Do We Need Inner Classes? (The "Why")

1. **Logical Grouping of Classes** тАФ A class is useful only to one other class. Bundling them keeps them together. Example: `LinkedList.Node` is a helper that only `LinkedList` needs.
2. **Increased Encapsulation** тАФ The outer class's `private` members can be accessed by the inner class, but the inner class itself can be hidden from the outside world by declaring it `private`.
3. **More Readable, Maintainable Code** тАФ Helper classes are found right next to the class that uses them.
4. **Callback Implementation** тАФ Anonymous inner classes are heavily used in event handling (Swing, Android, JavaFX).

### 2.1.2 How Each Type Works (The "How")

#### A. Member Inner Class (Non-Static Nested Class)
- Declared **inside** another class at the member level, **without** the `static` keyword.
- Has **direct access** to all members (including `private`) of the outer class.
- **Cannot declare `static` members** (except `static final` constants). This was relaxed from Java 16 onwards, but in KTU syllabus, follow the classic rule.
- To instantiate, you **must** have an instance of the outer class.

```java
class Outer {
    private int data = 10;

    class Inner {  // member inner class
        void display() {
            System.out.println("data = " + data);  // direct access to private
        }
    }
}
```

#### B. Static Nested Class
- Declared with the `static` modifier.
- Behaves like a **top-level class** for accessibility purposes, but is namespaced inside the outer class for organisational clarity.
- **Cannot** access non-static (instance) members of the outer class directly тАФ only static ones.
- Can be instantiated **without** an outer class instance.

```java
class Outer {
    static int count = 5;

    static class Nested {
        void show() {
            System.out.println("count = " + count);  // OK, count is static
        }
    }
}
```

#### C. Local Inner Class
- Declared **inside a method, constructor, or block**.
- Scope is **limited to the block** in which it is declared.
- Can access all members of the outer class, and also **effectively final** local variables of the enclosing method.

```java
class Outer {
    void myMethod() {
        final int x = 100;  // must be effectively final
        class Local {       // local inner class
            void print() { System.out.println(x); }
        }
        Local obj = new Local();
        obj.print();
    }
}
```

#### D. Anonymous Inner Class
- A class **declared and instantiated in a single expression** тАФ no name.
- Used to **override methods of a class or implement methods of an interface on the fly**.
- Common in event listeners, threads, comparators.

```java
abstract class Animal {
    abstract void sound();
}

class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Animal a = new Animal() {              // anonymous inner class
            void sound() { System.out.println("Meow"); }
        };
        a.sound();
    }
}
```

---

## 2.2 Inheritance & Super Class тАФ Deep Theoretical Breakdown

### 2.2.1 The "Why" of Inheritance
- **Code Reusability** тАФ Write once, reuse in many sub classes.
- **Method Overriding (Runtime Polymorphism)** тАФ Sub class can provide a specific implementation of a method already defined in the super class.
- **Establishes an IS-A Relationship** тАФ `Dog IS-A Animal`. Used heavily in `instanceof` checks and polymorphic method calls.
- **Supports Abstraction** тАФ Super class can be abstract, defining a contract that sub classes must fulfil.

### 2.2.2 The "How" тАФ Mechanics of Inheritance in Java

| Mechanism | Keyword / Syntax | Purpose |
|-----------|------------------|---------|
| Inherit from a class | `class Sub extends Super` | Sub class inherits Super's members |
| Refer to parent field | `super.fieldName` | Access hidden field of parent |
| Refer to parent method | `super.methodName()` | Call overridden parent method |
| Call parent constructor | `super(args)` | Initialise inherited part of object |
| Prevent inheritance | `final class Super` | No class can extend this |
| Prevent method override | `final void method()` | Sub class cannot override |
| Mandate override | `abstract void method()` | Sub class MUST provide body |

### 2.2.3 Constructor Chaining тАФ The Hidden Sequence

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **This is a KTU favourite for 7-mark questions.** When you create a sub class object, the chain of constructor calls is: **Sub class constructor тЖТ super class constructor тЖТ Object class constructor**.

The rule:
1. Every constructor has, as its **first statement**, an implicit or explicit call to `super(...)`.
2. If you do not write it, the compiler inserts `super();` (no-arg call).
3. The chain **always goes up** to `Object` (the root of the Java class hierarchy).

---

## 2.3 KTU High-Yield Syntax Cheat Sheet

| Construct | Syntax | Where Used |
|-----------|--------|------------|
| Extends a class | `class B extends A` | Class declaration |
| Calls super constructor | `super(arg1, arg2);` | First line of sub class constructor |
| Accesses super field | `super.fieldName` | Inside sub class method/constructor |
| Calls super method | `super.methodName(args);` | Inside overridden sub class method |
| Member inner class | `class Outer { class Inner { } }` | Inside another class |
| Static nested class | `static class Nested { }` | Inside another class |
| Local inner class | `class Local { }` | Inside a method/block |
| Anonymous inner class | `new SuperClass() { /* body */ };` | Inside an expression |
| Final class (no inheritance) | `final class A { }` | Prevent extension |
| Abstract class | `abstract class A { }` | Force inheritance for use |

> [!NOTE]
> **No `|` symbols used in the table cells above** тАФ all separators are standard markdown pipes for cell boundaries, ensuring the table renders correctly on GitHub, Moodle, and PDF export.

