## 3.1 Walkthrough 1: Member Inner Class (Full Code + Output)

### Code
```java
class CPU {
    double price;

    // constructor
    CPU(double price) {
        this.price = price;
    }

    // member inner class
    class Processor {
        int cores;
        String manufacturer;

        Processor(int cores, String manufacturer) {
            this.cores = cores;
            this.manufacturer = manufacturer;
        }

        void display() {
            // direct access to outer's private... wait, price is package-private
            // but we can still access it from inner class
            System.out.println("CPU Price: " + price);
            System.out.println("Processor Cores: " + cores);
            System.out.println("Manufacturer: " + manufacturer);
        }
    }
}

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Step 1: create outer object first
        CPU cpu = new CPU(45000.00);

        // Step 2: create inner object using outer object
        CPU.Processor proc = cpu.new Processor(8, "Intel");

        // Step 3: call method
        proc.display();
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Explanation (KTU Model Answer Style)

| Step | Code | Explanation |
|------|------|-------------|
| 1 | `class CPU { ... }` | Defines the outer (enclosing) class. |
| 2 | `class Processor { ... }` (inside CPU) | Declares a **member inner class** тАФ non-static, member-level. |
| 3 | `CPU cpu = new CPU(45000.00);` | Creates the outer class object тАФ **mandatory** before instantiating an inner class. |
| 4 | `CPU.Processor proc = cpu.new Processor(8, "Intel");` | Uses the **special syntax** `outerInstance.new InnerClass(...)` to create the inner class object. |
| 5 | `proc.display();` | Calls the method which has full access to the outer class's `price` field. |

### Expected Output
```
CPU Price: 45000.0
Processor Cores: 8
Manufacturer: Intel
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Marking Insight:** The syntax `outerObj.new Inner()` is the most-skipped line by students. It is **not** `new CPU.Processor()`. This is worth **1 mark** by itself in a 7-mark question.

