## 3.3 Walkthrough 3: Local Inner Class (Full Code + Output)

### Code
```java
class Outer {
    void greet() {
        String msg = "Hello";  // effectively final
        // local inner class inside a method
        class Local {
            void print() {
                System.out.println(msg);
            }
        }
        Local obj = new Local();
        obj.print();
    }
}

class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Outer().greet();
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Explanation

| Step | Code | Explanation |
|------|------|-------------|
| 1 | `void greet()` | The enclosing method. |
| 2 | `String msg = "Hello";` | A **local variable**. It must be **final or effectively final** to be captured by the local inner class. |
| 3 | `class Local { ... }` | A **local inner class** тАФ its scope is only inside `greet()`. |
| 4 | `Local obj = new Local();` | Instantiated and used **only within the method**. |
| 5 | `System.out.println(msg);` | The local inner class **captures** `msg` from the enclosing method's stack. |

### Expected Output
```
Hello
```

