## 3.4 Walkthrough 4: Anonymous Inner Class (Full Code + Output)

### Code
```java
interface Greeting {
    void sayHello();
}

class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // anonymous inner class implementing Greeting
        Greeting g = new Greeting() {
            public void sayHello() {
                System.out.println("Hello from anonymous class!");
            }
        };
        g.sayHello();
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Explanation

| Step | Code | Explanation |
|------|------|-------------|
| 1 | `interface Greeting` | An interface with one abstract method. |
| 2 | `new Greeting() { ... }` | Creates an **anonymous (unnamed) class** that **implements** `Greeting` on the fly. |
| 3 | `public void sayHello() { ... }` | Provides the implementation of the interface method. |
| 4 | `Greeting g = ...;` | The reference is of type `Greeting`, but the object is of the anonymous class. |
| 5 | `g.sayHello();` | Polymorphic call dispatches to the anonymous class's implementation. |

### Expected Output
```
Hello from anonymous class!
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Java 8 Note (for awareness):** From Java 8 onwards, this code can be replaced with a **lambda**: `Greeting g = () -> System.out.println("Hello!");`. However, KTU 2024 syllabus still teaches the anonymous inner class form as the foundation.

