## 3.5 Walkthrough 5: Inheritance & `super` Keyword (Full Code + Output)

### Code
```java
// Super class
class Animal {
    String name;

    Animal() {
        System.out.println("Animal constructor called");
    }

    Animal(String name) {
        this.name = name;
        System.out.println("Animal(String) constructor: " + name);
    }

    void speak() {
        System.out.println("Animal speaks");
    }
}

// Sub class
class Dog extends Animal {
    String breed;

    Dog() {
        // implicit super();   тЖТ calls Animal()
        System.out.println("Dog constructor called");
    }

    Dog(String name, String breed) {
        super(name);          // explicit call to Animal(String)
        this.breed = breed;
        System.out.println("Dog constructor: " + name + ", " + breed);
    }

    @Override
    void speak() {
        super.speak();        // call parent's version first
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}

class TestInherit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("--- Creating Dog() ---");
        Dog d1 = new Dog();

        System.out.println("\n--- Creating Dog(name, breed) ---");
        Dog d2 = new Dog("Bruno", "Labrador");

        System.out.println("\n--- Calling speak() ---");
        d2.speak();
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Trace

**Part 1: `new Dog();`**
1. Java sees `Dog()` constructor. First line is implicit `super();`.
2. Control jumps to `Animal()` тЖТ prints `"Animal constructor called"`.
3. Control returns to `Dog()` тЖТ prints `"Dog constructor called"`.

**Part 2: `new Dog("Bruno", "Labrador");`**
1. `Dog(String, String)` constructor begins.
2. First line is **explicit** `super(name);` тЖТ calls `Animal(String)`.
3. `Animal(String)` prints `"Animal(String) constructor: Bruno"`.
4. Returns to `Dog(...)`; `this.breed = breed;` executes.
5. Prints `"Dog constructor: Bruno, Labrador"`.

**Part 3: `d2.speak();`**
1. `Dog.speak()` executes.
2. First line: `super.speak();` тЖТ calls `Animal.speak()` тЖТ prints `"Animal speaks"`.
3. Then prints `"Dog barks"`.

### Expected Output
```
--- Creating Dog() ---
Animal constructor called
Dog constructor called

--- Creating Dog(name, breed) ---
Animal(String) constructor: Bruno
Dog constructor: Bruno, Labrador

--- Calling speak() ---
Animal speaks
Dog barks
```

### Constructor Chaining Diagram (Logical Sequence)

$$
\boxed{\text{main()} \;\longrightarrow\; \text{Dog()} \;\xrightarrow{\text{super}()} \; \text{Animal()} \;\xrightarrow{\text{super}()} \; \text{Object()}}
$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Board Examiner Note:** The flow `main тЖТ Dog тЖТ Animal тЖТ Object` is the **exact wording** expected in answer sheets. Writing it in this sequence fetches full marks for the constructor-chaining question.

