# 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 Mermaid Diagram 1: Java Inner Class Classification Tree

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Java Nested Classes] --> B[Static Nested Class]
    A --> C[Non-Static Inner Classes]
    C --> D[Member Inner Class]
    C --> E[Local Inner Class]
    C --> F[Anonymous Inner Class]

    B --> B1["Declared with static keyword"]
    B --> B2["Cannot access non-static outer members"]
    B --> B3["Instantiated without outer object"]

    D --> D1["Member level inside another class"]
    D --> D2["Can access all outer members"]
    D --> D3["Needs outer instance to instantiate"]

    E --> E1["Declared inside a method or block"]
    E --> E2["Scope limited to enclosing block"]
    E --> E3["Accesses effectively final local variables"]

    F --> F1["Declared and instantiated in one expression"]
    F --> F2["No class name"]
    F --> F3["Common in event handling"]
```

### Interpretation
The diagram classifies all four types of inner (nested) classes in Java, with the **static nested class** as a separate branch from the three non-static variants. Each leaf shows the defining characteristics тАФ **memorise this tree** for viva questions.

---

## 4.2 Mermaid Diagram 2: Inheritance & Constructor Chaining Flow

```mermaid
graph TD
    OBJ[Object Class] --> ANIMAL[Super Class: Animal]
    ANIMAL --> DOG[Sub Class: Dog]

    DOG --> D1[Inherits name field]
    DOG --> D2[Inherits speak method]
    DOG --> D3[Adds breed field]
    DOG --> D4[Overrides speak method]

    DOG --> C1["super(name) calls Animal"]
    ANIMAL --> C2["super() calls Object"]

    FLOW[main method] --> INST[Dog dog = new Dog]
    INST --> S1[Dog constructor starts]
    S1 --> S2[super call goes to Animal]
    S2 --> S3[super call goes to Object]
    S3 --> S4[Object initialised first]
    S4 --> S5[Animal initialised next]
    S5 --> S6[Dog initialised last]
```

### Interpretation
This diagram visually traces the **constructor chaining** mechanism: when a `Dog` object is created, the JVM first initialises the `Object` class (root of Java class hierarchy), then `Animal`, and finally `Dog`. The `super` keyword is the vehicle that drives this chain.

---

## 4.3 Mermaid Diagram 3: Inner Class Access Model (Block Architecture)

```mermaid
graph LR
    OUTER[Outer Class] --> PRI[Private Members x and y]
    OUTER --> INNER[Inner Class Body]
    INNER --> ACC[Direct access to x and y]
    INNER --> METH[Method display]
    METH --> OUT[Prints x and y]

    OUTSIDE[Outside World] -.Cannot directly access x and y.-> PRI
    OUTSIDE --> INST[Must use outer.new Inner to instantiate]
    INST --> INNER
```

### Interpretation
This is the **Block-Level Functional Architecture** of how encapsulation works with inner classes:
- The **outer class** owns the private members.
- The **inner class** has privileged, direct access.
- The **outside world** cannot access the private members directly, and must go through the inner class instance (which itself requires an outer instance).

---

## 4.4 Mermaid Diagram 4: `super` Keyword тАФ Three Use-Cases

```mermaid
graph TD
    SUPER[The super keyword] --> U1[Use 1: super field]
    SUPER --> U2[Use 2: super method]
    SUPER --> U3[Use 3: super constructor]

    U1 --> U1A[Access hidden super class field]
    U1A --> U1B[Example super dot data]

    U2 --> U2A[Call overridden super class method]
    U2A --> U2B[Example super dot display]

    U3 --> U3A[Invoke super class constructor]
    U3A --> U3B[Example super args]
    U3B --> U3C[MUST be first line in sub constructor]
```

### Interpretation
The `super` keyword has **exactly three valid uses** in Java. This diagram is a high-yield revision tool тАФ KTU examiners often ask *"List the uses of super keyword"* as a 3-mark Part A question.

---

## 4.5 Mermaid Diagram 5: Block Diagram of Inheritance Memory Model

```mermaid
graph TD
    MEM[Heap Memory] --> OBJ1[Dog Object]
    OBJ1 --> PART1[Super Class Portion: Animal part]
    OBJ1 --> PART2[Sub Class Portion: Dog part]

    PART1 --> F1[Inherited field: name]
    PART1 --> M1[Inherited method: speak]

    PART2 --> F2[New field: breed]
    PART2 --> M2[Overridden method: speak]

    THIS[this refers to entire OBJ1]
    SUP[super refers only to PART1]
```

### Interpretation
This is a **memory model block diagram** showing that:
- A single `Dog` object in memory contains BOTH the super class portion and the sub class portion.
- `this` тЖТ refers to the **whole object**.
- `super` тЖТ refers to **only the super class portion** of that object.
- This is why `super.fieldName` accesses the parent's field even if the sub class has hidden it.
