### Question 2 [KTU University Exam тАФ Dec 2023]
**Explain the three uses of the `super` keyword in Java with examples.**

#### Model Answer (3 Marks)

The `super` keyword in Java is a reference variable that refers to the immediate **parent (super) class object**. It has three uses:

**1. To refer to a super class field (when hidden by sub class):**
```java
class A {
    int x = 10;
}
class B extends A {
    int x = 20;
    void show() {
        System.out.println(super.x);  // prints 10
        System.out.println(x);        // prints 20
    }
}
```

**2. To call an overridden super class method:**
```java
class A {
    void display() { System.out.println("A"); }
}
class B extends A {
    @Override
    void display() {
        super.display();  // calls A's display
        System.out.println("B");
    }
}
```

**3. To invoke a super class constructor:**
```java
class A {
    A() { System.out.println("A constructor"); }
}
class B extends A {
    B() {
        super();  // calls A's constructor
        System.out.println("B constructor");
    }
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The call `super()` **must be the first statement** in the sub class constructor. If omitted, the compiler inserts a no-argument `super()` automatically.

