### **Question B (14 Marks)** [Alternative Choice тАФ KTU University Exam тАФ Dec 2023 Style]

#### (a) [7 Marks] What is inheritance in Java? Explain the role of the `super` keyword in accessing super class members with examples.

**Model Answer:**

**Definition:**
Inheritance is the OOP mechanism in Java by which a class (the **sub class** or **child class**) acquires the fields and methods of another class (the **super class** or **parent class**) using the `extends` keyword. It enables **code reuse** and establishes an **IS-A relationship** between classes.

**General Syntax:**
```java
class SuperClass {
    // members
}
class SubClass extends SuperClass {
    // inherits + adds new + overrides
}
```

**Role of the `super` Keyword:**
The `super` keyword is a reference variable in Java that refers to the **immediate super class object**. It is used in **three** scenarios:

**(i) Accessing hidden fields of the super class:**
```java
class Employee {
    double salary = 50000;
}
class Manager extends Employee {
    double salary = 80000;  // hides parent's salary

    void printSalaries() {
        System.out.println("Manager salary: " + salary);       // 80000
        System.out.println("Employee salary: " + super.salary); // 50000
    }
}
```

**(ii) Calling overridden super class methods:**
```java
class Animal {
    void sound() { System.out.println("Animal sound"); }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        super.sound();  // call parent version
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}
```

**(iii) Invoking super class constructors:**
```java
class Person {
    Person(String name) {
        System.out.println("Person: " + name);
    }
}
class Student extends Person {
    Student(String name, int roll) {
        super(name);   // call Person(String)
        System.out.println("Student roll: " + roll);
    }
}
```

**Key Rules:**
1. `super` cannot be used in a `static` method.
2. `super()` must be the **first statement** in a constructor.
3. If not written, the compiler inserts a **no-argument `super()`** automatically.

> [!TIP]
> **Mark Distribution (7 marks):** 2 marks for inheritance definition + syntax, 3 marks for the three `super` uses (1 mark each), 2 marks for rules/key points.

#### (b) [7 Marks] Write a Java program to demonstrate the use of (i) member inner class, (ii) anonymous inner class with an interface, and (iii) local inner class. Show the output for each.

**Model Answer:**

**(i) Member Inner Class:**
```java
class College {
    String name = "KTU";

    class Department {
        String dept = "CSE";
        void display() {
