## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

In Object-Oriented Programming using Java, a **Sub Class** (also called a *derived class*, *child class*, or *extended class*) is a class that **inherits** attributes (fields) and behaviors (methods) from another class, referred to as the **Super Class** (or *base class* / *parent class*). The mechanism of defining a subclass is called **Inheritance**, and in Java it is achieved using the reserved keyword `extends`.

According to the KTU 2024 Scheme syllabus for Module 2 (Inheritance and Packages), a subclass:

- Acquired the **public** and **protected** members of its direct superclass automatically.
- May introduce its own **new fields, methods, and constructors** in addition to the inherited ones.
- May **override** inherited methods to provide specialized behavior (a concept formalized as *Runtime Polymorphism*).
- Establishes a strict **"IS-A"** relationship with the superclass (e.g., a `Dog` IS-A `Animal`).

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight (Module 2):**
> A subclass is the cornerstone of inheritance. Java supports **single inheritance** for classes тАФ meaning any subclass can extend **only one** direct superclass. Multiple inheritance of *type* is, however, supported through **interfaces** (covered later in the module).

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy тАФ The Family Tree

Imagine a real-world **family tree**:

| Real-World Concept | Java Equivalent |
|---|---|
| Parents pass traits (eye color, surname) to children | Superclass passes fields and methods to subclass |
| Children may have their own unique skills | Subclass may add new fields/methods |
| Children may pursue the same career differently | Subclass may override inherited methods |
| Family surname is shared | Common superclass reference |

For example, consider a parent class `Vehicle`. A subclass `Car` automatically "inherits" properties like `speed` and `fuelType`, and behaviors like `start()` and `stop()`. However, a `Car` may add its own properties such as `numberOfDoors` and override `start()` to display *"Car engine started"*, whereas the parent `Vehicle.start()` might display a generic message.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Crucial Distinction:**
> A subclass is **not a copy** of the superclass тАФ it is an *extension*. The superclass members are physically present only once in memory, while each subclass object can access them as if they were its own.

### 1.3 Key Terminology

- **Super Class** тАУ The class whose features are inherited.
- **Sub Class** тАУ The class that inherits features from the superclass.
- **Reusability** тАУ The fundamental OOD principle that inheritance delivers; code of the superclass is reused by the subclass.
- **Generalization** тАУ The process of extracting common features into a superclass.
- **Specialization** тАУ The process of creating a subclass to add or modify behavior.

