## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference Sheet

### 2.1 Operational Logic of Subclass Creation

The creation and behavior of a Java subclass can be broken down into the following structured steps:

1. **Declaration Phase** тАФ The subclass is declared using the syntax:
   `class SubClassName extends SuperClassName { ... }`
2. **Member Ingestion Phase** тАФ The Java compiler conceptually copies all non-private members of the superclass into the subclass. (Physically, they are accessed via an implicit reference.)
3. **Extension Phase** тАФ The programmer adds new fields, new methods, or overrides inherited methods.
4. **Object Instantiation Phase** тАФ When `new SubClass()` is executed, the JVM allocates memory in the **heap** and the constructor chain executes тАФ the superclass constructor runs **first**, followed by the subclass constructor.
5. **Method Dispatch Phase** тАФ When an overridden method is invoked, the JVM uses **Dynamic Method Dispatch** (Late Binding) to decide which version to run, based on the *actual* object type, not the reference type.

### 2.2 The "Why" Behind Each Step

- **Why `extends`?** Java's designers chose single inheritance to avoid the *Diamond Problem* (ambiguity when two parents define the same method).
- **Why does the superclass constructor run first?** So that inherited fields are *initialized* before the subclass constructor body executes, ensuring a fully-constructed base before specialization.
- **Why allow overriding?** Because a subclass must be allowed to provide a *more specific* behavior than the general contract of the superclass тАФ the essence of polymorphism.

### 2.3 KTU High-Yield Reference Table

| Concept | Java Construct | Allowed? | KTU Board Note |
|---|---|---|---|
| Declaring a subclass | `class B extends A` | Yes | Java does not support multiple class inheritance |
| Inheriting `public` members | Automatic | Yes | Accessible anywhere |
| Inheriting `protected` members | Automatic | Yes | Accessible via inheritance + same package |
| Inheriting `private` members | Not directly | No | Accessible only via public/protected getters |
| Inheriting constructors | Not inherited | No | Called via `super(...)` |
| Inheriting `static` members | Yes (shared) | Yes | Belong to the class, not the object |
| Inheriting `final` class | Cannot extend | No | `final` class cannot be a superclass |
| Overriding a `final` method | Not allowed | No | Compile-time error |
| Overriding a `static` method | Method hiding (not overriding) | Allowed with caution | Polymorphism does not apply |
| Using `super.field` / `super.method()` | Explicit parent access | Yes | Resolves ambiguity |
| Using `super(args)` | Parent constructor call | Yes | Must be the **first** statement |

### 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

Subclassing is the foundation of nearly every large-scale Java framework:

- **Spring Framework** тАФ `CrudRepository<T, ID>` is a generic superclass extended by user-defined repository interfaces.
- **JavaFX / Swing GUI** тАФ `Button` extends `ButtonBase` extends `Control` extends `Region` extends `Parent` extends `Node`.
- **JDBC** тАФ `PreparedStatement extends Statement` тАФ subclass adds precompilation benefits.
- **Android SDK** тАФ `AppCompatActivity extends FragmentActivity extends ComponentActivity extends androidx.core.app.ComponentActivity` тАФ deep subclass chains define lifecycle behavior.

> [!TIP]
> **Examiner's Heuristic:** When asked "What is a subclass?", always mention **three** properties together: (1) `extends` keyword, (2) IS-A relationship, (3) inherits *non-private* members. This triplet is the most-credited answer pattern in KTU valuation.

