## 3. Step-by-Step Analytical Walkthroughs & Code Derivations

### 3.1 Walkthrough 1 тАФ Minimal Subclass Declaration

**Problem:** Demonstrate the creation of a subclass `Dog` that extends a superclass `Animal`.

**Step 1 тАФ Define the superclass:**

```java
class Animal {
    String name;

    public void eat() {
        System.out.println(name + " is eating.");
    }

    public void sleep() {
        System.out.println(name + " is sleeping.");
    }
}
```

**Step 2 тАФ Define the subclass using `extends`:**

```java
class Dog extends Animal {
    String breed;

    public void bark() {
        System.out.println(name + " of breed " + breed + " is barking.");
    }
}
```

**Step 3 тАФ Instantiate and exercise inherited + new members:**

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog d = new Dog();
        d.name   = "Buddy";
        d.breed  = "Labrador";
        d.eat();    // inherited from Animal
        d.sleep();  // inherited from Animal
        d.bark();   // defined in Dog
    }
}
```

**Step 4 тАФ Trace output:**

```
Buddy is eating.
Buddy is sleeping.
Buddy of breed Labrador is barking.
```

**Inference:** The `Dog` object accessed `name` (inherited field) and `eat()`/`sleep()` (inherited methods) as if they were its own, while also exposing the new `bark()` and `breed`.

---

### 3.2 Walkthrough 2 тАФ Constructor Chaining with `super()`

**Problem:** Show how a subclass constructor explicitly invokes the superclass constructor.

```java
class Person {
    String name;
    int    age;

    Person(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age  = age;
        System.out.println("Person constructor called.");
    }
}

class Student extends Person {
    int rollNo;

    Student(String name, int age, int rollNo) {
        super(name, age);          // explicit call to parent constructor
        this.rollNo = rollNo;
        System.out.println("Student constructor called.");
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name + ", Age: " + age + ", Roll: " + rollNo);
    }
}
```

**Step-by-step trace of `new Student("Anu", 20, 45)`:**

- Line 1: JVM pushes `Student` constructor onto the call stack.
- Line 2: `super(name, age)` is encountered тЖТ JVM invokes `Person` constructor.
- Line 3: `Person` constructor executes тЖТ initializes `name` and `age`; prints `"Person constructor called."`.
- Line 4: Control returns to `Student` constructor; `this.rollNo = rollNo` executes.
- Line 5: Prints `"Student constructor called."`.

**Output:**

```
Person constructor called.
Student constructor called.
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rule:** `super(...)` (or `this(...)` if chaining within the same class) must be the **very first statement** in a constructor. If omitted, the compiler *implicitly* inserts `super();` (no-argument super call), which fails to compile if the superclass has no no-arg constructor.

---

### 3.3 Walkthrough 3 тАФ Method Overriding in a Subclass

**Problem:** Override `speak()` in `Dog` to provide a specialized behavior.

```java
class Animal {
    void speak() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes a sound.");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void speak() {
        super.speak();              // optionally invoke parent version
        System.out.println("Dog barks.");
    }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
    @Override
    void speak() {
        System.out.println("Cat meows.");
    }
}
```

**Demonstration of Dynamic Method Dispatch:**

```java
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Animal a1 = new Dog();   // upcasting
        Animal a2 = new Cat();

        a1.speak();  // calls Dog's overridden version
        a2.speak();  // calls Cat's overridden version
    }
}
```

**Output:**

```
Animal makes a sound.
Dog barks.
Cat meows.
```

**Analytical Reasoning:**

- Even though the *reference type* is `Animal`, the JVM invokes the method based on the *actual object type* (`Dog` or `Cat`).
- This is **Runtime Polymorphism** тАФ a direct consequence of subclassing and method overriding.

> [!WARNING]
> **Common KTU Mistake:** Writing `@Override` is **optional** but strongly recommended. Forgetting to write `@Override` does **not** cause a compile error if signatures match тАФ but if you mistype the method name, you accidentally *overload* instead of override, and polymorphism silently breaks. Always include `@Override` for safety.

---

### 3.4 Walkthrough 4 тАФ Type Compatibility and the "IS-A" Test

**Rule (formalized):**

$$\text{If } B \text{ extends } A, \text{ then } B \text{ IS-A } A \text{ (always true at compile time)}$$

This produces the following **assignment compatibility matrix:**

| Reference Type тЖТ  /  Object Type тЖУ | A | B (subclass of A) | C (unrelated) |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A** (superclass) | тЬФ Allowed | тЬФ Allowed (upcasting, implicit) | тЬШ Compile error |
| **B** (subclass)  | тЬШ Compile error (downcast needed) | тЬФ Allowed | тЬШ Compile error |
| **C** (unrelated) | тЬШ Compile error | тЬШ Compile error | тЬФ Allowed |

> [!NOTE]
> Upcasting (subclass тЖТ superclass) is **implicit and safe**. Downcasting (superclass тЖТ subclass) requires an explicit cast and can throw `ClassCastException` at runtime if the actual object is not of the target type.

