**(b) With a neat program, demonstrate constructor chaining between a superclass and a subclass using the `super` keyword. Explain the order of execution. (7 marks)**

**Model Solution:**

```java
class Account {
    String holder;
    double balance;

    Account(String holder, double balance) {       // parameterized constructor
        this.holder  = holder;
        this.balance = balance;
        System.out.println("Account constructor executed.");
    }
}

class SavingsAccount extends Account {
    double interestRate;

    SavingsAccount(String holder, double balance, double rate) {
        super(holder, balance);                    // calls Account(String, double)
        this.interestRate = rate;
        System.out.println("SavingsAccount constructor executed.");
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Holder: " + holder + ", Balance: " + balance
                           + ", Rate: " + interestRate);
    }
}

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SavingsAccount sa = new SavingsAccount("Anu", 10000, 4.5);
        sa.display();
    }
}
```

**Order of execution for `new SavingsAccount(...)`:**

1. `SavingsAccount` constructor invoked.
2. `super(holder, balance)` transfers control to `Account(String, double)`.
3. `Account` constructor initializes `holder` and `balance`.
4. Control returns to `SavingsAccount`; `interestRate` initialized.
5. Object reference returned.

**Output:**

```
Account constructor executed.
SavingsAccount constructor executed.
Holder: Anu, Balance: 10000.0, Rate: 4.5
```

> **Mark split:** Program тАФ 3, `super()` call тАФ 2, Execution order explanation тАФ 2.

