**Q B. [KTU University Exam тАФ Dec 2023, Module 2, 14 Marks тАФ Alternative]**

**(a) What is method overriding? Demonstrate it with a Java program showing dynamic method dispatch between superclass and subclass references. (7 marks)**

**Model Solution:**

**Method Overriding** occurs when a subclass provides a *new implementation* for a method already defined in its superclass, using the **same signature** (name, parameter list, return type).

```java
class Employee {
    double computeBonus(double salary) {
        return salary * 0.10;
    }
}

class Manager extends Employee {
    @Override
    double computeBonus(double salary) {
        return salary * 0.25;       // higher bonus for managers
    }
}

class Intern extends Employee {
    @Override
    double computeBonus(double salary) {
        return salary * 0.02;
    }
}

public class Payroll {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee e1 = new Manager();   // upcasting
        Employee e2 = new Intern();

        System.out.println("Manager bonus: " + e1.computeBonus(50000));
        System.out.println("Intern bonus:  " + e2.computeBonus(50000));
    }
}
```

**Output:**

```
Manager bonus: 12500.0
Intern bonus: 1000.0
```

**Dynamic Method Dispatch:** Even though both references are of type `Employee`, the JVM resolves `computeBonus()` at *runtime* based on the actual object class тАФ `Manager` or `Intern`. This is the runtime polymorphism powered by subclassing.

> **Mark split:** Definition тАФ 2, Program тАФ 3, Output + explanation тАФ 2.

---

**(b) Explain the various uses of the `super` keyword in Java with examples. How does it differ from the `this` keyword? (7 marks)**

**Model Solution:**

The `super` keyword in Java refers to the **immediate parent class object**. It has **three** primary uses:

**Use 1 тАФ `super.field` to access hidden parent fields:**

```java
class A { int x = 10; }
class B extends A {
    int x = 20;
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Sub x  = " + x);        // 20
        System.out.println("Super x = " + super.x); // 10
    }
}
```

**Use 2 тАФ `super.method()` to invoke overridden parent methods:**

```java
class A { void greet() { System.out.println("Hello from A"); } }
class B extends A {
    @Override
    void greet() {
        super.greet();
        System.out.println("Hello from B");
    }
}
```

**Use 3 тАФ `super(args)` to invoke a parent constructor (must be the first line):**

```java
class A { A(int x) { System.out.println("A: " + x); } }
class B extends A {
    B() { super(100); System.out.println("B"); }
}
```

**Comparison Table тАФ `super` vs `this`:**

| Aspect | `this` | `super` |
|---|---|---|
| Refers to | Current object | Immediate parent class object |
| Field access | `this.field` | `super.field` |
| Method access | `this.method()` | `super.method()` |
| Constructor | `this(args)` (same class) | `super(args)` (parent class) |
| Position rule | First statement of constructor | First statement of constructor |
| Cannot coexist | `this()` and `super()` cannot both be used in the same constructor тАФ only one may appear as the first line. |

> **Mark split:** Three uses тАФ 3, Examples тАФ 2, Comparison table тАФ 2.

