# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

**Constructor Calling Order** refers to the deterministic sequence in which constructors are invoked by the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) during object creation. The order is governed by two fundamental mechanisms:

1. **Constructor Chaining** тАФ Within a single class, an overloaded constructor can invoke another constructor of the **same class** using the keyword `this(...)`.
2. **Inheritance-Based Invocation** тАФ When an object of a subclass is created, the constructor of its **direct superclass** is always invoked (either implicitly or explicitly) using `super(...)`, before the subclass constructor body executes.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Board Definition (Reproduce verbatim in exams):**
> *"The calling order of constructors in Java follows a strict top-down inheritance chain. The superclass constructor is always executed before the subclass constructor. The chain continues upward until the `java.lang.Object` class constructor is reached, after which control returns downward to the original calling constructor."*

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy тАФ "Building a Multi-Story House"

Imagine constructing a **3-story building** where each floor inherits the strength of the one below it.

| Construction Step | Java Equivalent |
|---|---|
| Laying the **foundation** first | `Object` class constructor executes |
| Building the **Ground Floor** | `Grandparent` class constructor executes |
| Building the **First Floor** | `Parent` class constructor executes |
| Building the **Top Floor** | `Child` class constructor executes |

You **cannot** build the First Floor before the Ground Floor тАФ just as a child constructor **cannot** complete its initialization before the parent constructor has finished.

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Insight:** The JVM calls constructors in **reverse hierarchical order** тАФ from the **root (Object)** down to the **most-derived (Child)**. This guarantees that inherited members are fully initialized before the subclass uses them.

## 1.3 Three Critical Rules (Board-Favorite Points)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> 1. **`super()` is always the first executable statement** in a constructor (whether written explicitly or inserted implicitly by the compiler).
> 2. **`this()` and `super()` cannot appear together** in the same constructor тАФ both must be the first statement.
> 3. If a constructor does **not** explicitly call `super(...)`, the compiler **automatically inserts** a call to the **no-argument constructor** of the superclass.

