**(b) Explain any four important rules that govern the use of `this()` and `super()` in Java constructors with suitable code snippets.** **(7 marks)**

**Model Answer тАФ Four Rules:**

**Rule 1 тАФ First-Statement Mandate**
Both `this()` and `super()` must be the **first executable statement** in a constructor.
```java
Student(int r) {
    System.out.println("roll");   // тЭМ COMPILE ERROR тАФ super() must be first
    super();                       // тЭМ
}
Student(int r) {
    super();                       // тЬЕ Correct
    System.out.println("roll");
}
```

**Rule 2 тАФ Mutual Exclusivity**
A constructor can use **either** `this()` **or** `super()`, but never both.
```java
Child() {
    super();       // тЭМ COMPILE ERROR тАФ cannot coexist with this()
    this(10);
}
```

**Rule 3 тАФ Implicit Insertion of `super()`**
If neither is written, the compiler **automatically inserts** `super();` (no-arg parent constructor call).
```java
class Parent { Parent(String s) { } }
class Child extends Parent {
    Child() { }     // тЭМ COMPILE ERROR тАФ no Parent() exists
}
```

**Rule 4 тАФ `this()` Enables Chained Initialization**
`this()` reduces code duplication by centralizing initialization in one "master" constructor.
```java
Box(int l, int b, int h) { /* master: assigns all fields */ }
Box()             { this(0, 0, 0); }    // delegates
Box(int size)     { this(size, size, size); }   // delegates
```

