# Section 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 Structural Anatomy of an Abstract Class

An abstract class in Java is composed of **four categories of members**. Understanding which combinations are legal is the most heavily tested area in KTU Module 2.

### 2.1.1 Member Categories Inside an Abstract Class

**Category 1 тАФ Abstract Members (Unimplemented Contracts)**
- Abstract instance methods (the only legal form of abstract member).

**Category 2 тАФ Concrete Members (Shared Reusable Code)**
- Concrete instance methods with full bodies.
- `static` methods (class-level utilities, accessible via class name).
- `final` methods (cannot be overridden by subclasses).
- Instance variables, static variables, final variables.

**Category 3 тАФ Constructor Members**
- Default no-arg constructor (auto-supplied if no constructor is written).
- Parameterized constructors (used by subclasses to initialize inherited state).

**Category 4 тАФ Nested Type Members**
- Nested abstract classes, nested concrete classes, nested interfaces, enums.

### 2.1.2 The Legal vs. Illegal Combinations Matrix

The following combinations are **syntactically illegal** in Java and are favourite KTU spot-error questions:

| Modifier Combination | Abstract Method | Concrete Method | Reason for Illegality |
|---|---|---|---|
| `abstract` + `static` | тЭМ Illegal | тЬЕ Legal | Static methods cannot be overridden; abstract requires overriding. |
| `abstract` + `final` | тЭМ Illegal | тЬЕ Legal | Final methods cannot be overridden; abstract requires overriding. |
| `abstract` + `private` | тЭМ Illegal | тЬЕ Legal | Private methods are invisible to subclasses; abstract requires visibility. |
| `abstract` + `synchronized` | тЭМ Illegal | тЬЕ Legal | Synchronization is an implementation detail, not a contract. |
| `abstract` + `native` | тЭМ Illegal | тЬЕ Legal | Native implies JNI body exists; abstract forbids a body. |
| `abstract` + `strictfp` | тЭМ Illegal | тЬЕ Legal | Same reasoning as `native`. |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Memory Hook:** *"Abstract = must be overridden. Static / final / private = cannot be overridden. These two forces are mutually exclusive, hence illegal."*

---

## 2.2 Mechanism of Enforcement (How Java Compilers Check Abstraction)

The Java compiler performs **two-phase enforcement** when processing a class that extends an abstract class:

**Phase 1 тАФ Class-Level Check:** If a class is declared `abstract`, compilation is allowed regardless of whether abstract methods are present.

**Phase 2 тАФ Method-Resolution Check:** If a non-abstract class extends an abstract class, the compiler walks up the inheritance chain and verifies that **every inherited abstract method has been provided an implementation** in *some* class along the chain. If even one abstract method remains unimplemented, the subclass **must be marked abstract**, or compilation fails.

This mechanism guarantees the **Liskov Substitution Principle** at the bytecode level: any object instantiated from the hierarchy will be a fully functional, type-complete entity.

---

## 2.3 Abstract Class vs. Concrete Class тАФ The Complete Comparison

This is one of the most frequently appearing **3-mark comparison questions** in KTU exams.

| Property | Abstract Class | Concrete Class |
|---|---|---|
| Keyword | Declared with `abstract` | No special keyword |
| Instantiation | тЭМ Cannot use `new` | тЬЕ Can use `new` |
| Abstract Methods | тЬЕ May contain | тЭМ Cannot contain |
| Concrete Methods | тЬЕ May contain | тЬЕ May contain |
| Constructors | тЬЕ Allowed | тЬЕ Allowed |
| `main()` Method | тЬЕ Allowed | тЬЕ Allowed |
| Inheritance Purpose | Provides partial implementation + contract | Provides full implementation |
| Object Count in App | Objects created via concrete subclasses | Objects created directly |
| Use Case | Generalization / template | Specialization / leaf nodes |

---

## 2.4 Abstract Class vs. Interface (Module 2 / Module 3 Bridge)

Although interfaces are introduced later in the syllabus, KTU examiners often draw a comparison expecting a foundational answer.

| Property | Abstract Class | Interface |
|---|---|---|
| Keyword | `abstract class` | `interface` |
| Methods | Abstract + concrete | Abstract (pre-Java 8) / default + static (Java 8+) |
| Variables | Any type | Implicitly `public static final` |
| Inheritance | Single (`extends`) | Multiple (`implements`) |
| Access Modifiers | Any | Implicitly `public` |
| Constructor | тЬЕ Yes | тЭМ No |
| When to Choose | Shared code + partial contract | Pure contract / multiple inheritance |

> [!TIP]
> **KTU Board Tip:** When asked to choose, the rule of thumb is тАФ *"Use an abstract class when your subclasses share **code** AND a **contract**; use an interface when they share only a **contract**."*

---

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Applications of Abstract Classes

| Domain | Abstract Class Example | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| **GUI Frameworks** | `java.awt.Component` (legacy) | Defines rendering contract `paint(Graphics)`; concrete subclasses (Button, Canvas) provide drawing logic. |
| **Template Method Pattern** | `javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet` | Defines `service()` skeleton; subclasses override `doGet()`, `doPost()`. |
| **JDBC** | `java.sql.Connection` (interface) / abstract wrappers | Standardizes database access contract. |
| **Collections** | `java.util.AbstractList` | Provides default implementations for `List` interface. |
| **Game Development** | `GameCharacter` | Declares `attack()`, `defend()`; subclasses (Warrior, Mage) implement differently. |
| **Banking Systems** | `BankAccount` | Declares `calculateInterest()`; subclasses (SavingsAccount, CurrentAccount) override. |

---

## 2.6 KTU High-Yield Keyword Cheat Sheet (Quick-Reference Table)

| Keyword / Phrase | KTU Expected Definition |
|---|---|
| `abstract` keyword | Declares a class or method as incomplete. |
| Abstract method | Method signature ending in `;` with no body. |
| Concrete class | Fully implemented class; can be instantiated. |
| Partial implementation | Some methods implemented, others left abstract. |
| Contract enforcement | Compiler mandates overriding of abstract methods. |
| `super()` call | Subclass constructor invoking abstract-class constructor. |
| Template method | Concrete method in abstract class that calls abstract methods. |
| Generalization | Abstract class captures common features of subclasses. |
| Specialization | Subclass provides specific implementations. |
