# Section 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Worked Example 1: The Shape Hierarchy (Module 2 Standard Problem)

This is the **canonical KTU Module 2 problem** on abstract classes. We will build it incrementally, with every Java line explained.

### 3.1.1 Step 1 тАФ Problem Statement

> *"Design a Java program using an abstract class `Shape` with an abstract method `area()`. Create two concrete subclasses `Circle` and `Rectangle` that compute their respective areas. Use polymorphism to call `area()` on an array of shapes."*

### 3.1.2 Step 2 тАФ Class Design (UML-to-Java Mapping)

| Class | Type | Members |
|---|---|---|
| `Shape` | Abstract | `abstract double area();` , `void display();` |
| `Circle` | Concrete extends `Shape` | `radius`, override `area()` |
| `Rectangle` | Concrete extends `Shape` | `length`, `width`, override `area()` |
| `ShapeDemo` | Concrete (driver) | `main()` method |

### 3.1.3 Step 3 тАФ Complete Java Program with Line-by-Line Analysis

```java
// File: Shape.java
// STEP A: Declaring the abstract superclass
abstract class Shape {
    // Abstract method тАФ no body, ends with semicolon
    // CONTRACT: every concrete subclass MUST provide area() implementation
    abstract double area();

    // Concrete helper method тАФ shared across all subclasses
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Area = " + area());
    }
}

// File: Circle.java
// STEP B: First concrete subclass implementing the contract
class Circle extends Shape {
    double radius;

    Circle(double radius) {
        this.radius = radius;          // initialize instance state
    }

    // MANDATORY OVERRIDE тАФ provides Circle-specific area computation
    @Override
    double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }
}

// File: Rectangle.java
// STEP C: Second concrete subclass implementing the contract
class Rectangle extends Shape {
    double length, width;

    Rectangle(double length, double width) {
        this.length = length;
        this.width = width;
    }

    // MANDATORY OVERRIDE тАФ provides Rectangle-specific area computation
    @Override
    double area() {
        return length * width;
    }
}

// File: ShapeDemo.java
// STEP D: Driver class demonstrating runtime polymorphism
public class ShapeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // POLYMORPHISM: Shape reference can hold any subclass object
        Shape s1 = new Circle(5.0);
        Shape s2 = new Rectangle(4.0, 6.0);

        // Dynamic method dispatch тАФ correct area() invoked at runtime
        s1.display();    // Output: Area = 78.5398...
        s2.display();    // Output: Area = 24.0
    }
}
```

### 3.1.4 Step 4 тАФ Logical Flow Analysis (Execution Trace)

| Line | Action | Memory Effect | Output |
|---|---|---|---|
| `Shape s1 = new Circle(5.0);` | Allocates `Circle` on heap; `s1` references it. | Heap: Circle{radius=5.0} | тАФ |
| `Shape s2 = new Rectangle(4.0, 6.0);` | Allocates `Rectangle` on heap. | Heap: Rectangle{length=4, width=6} | тАФ |
| `s1.display();` | Compiler resolves `display()` to `Shape`. At runtime, JVM sees actual object is `Circle`, calls `Circle.area()`. | тАФ | `Area = 78.5398...` |
| `s2.display();` | JVM dispatches to `Rectangle.area()`. | тАФ | `Area = 24.0` |

### 3.1.5 Step 5 тАФ Common Compilation Errors to Avoid

> [!WARNING]
> **Compiler Errors That Cause Mark Deductions in KTU Valuation:**
> 1. Forgetting `@Override` annotation тАФ *not a compile error, but loses style marks.*
> 2. Writing a body for `area()` in `Shape` тАФ **compile error:** *"Abstract methods cannot have a body."*
> 3. Declaring `Shape` without `abstract` but having an abstract method тАФ **compile error.**
> 4. Forgetting to override `area()` in `Circle` or `Rectangle` тАФ **compile error:** *"Circle is not abstract and does not override abstract method area() in Shape."*
> 5. Using `private` for `area()` in `Shape` тАФ **compile error** due to illegal modifier combo.

