## 3.3 Worked Example 3: Template Method Pattern (The Crown Jewel of Abstract Classes)

This is a **high-yield KTU concept** showing how abstract classes implement a famous design pattern.

```java
abstract class Game {
    // TEMPLATE METHOD тАФ final, cannot be overridden
    // Defines the algorithm skeleton; calls abstract primitives
    final void play() {
        initialize();
        startPlay();
        endPlay();
    }

    abstract void initialize();
    abstract void startPlay();
    abstract void endPlay();
}

class Cricket extends Game {
    @Override void initialize()   { System.out.println("Cricket Game Initialized"); }
    @Override void startPlay()    { System.out.println("Cricket Game Started"); }
    @Override void endPlay()      { System.out.println("Cricket Game Finished"); }
}

class Football extends Game {
    @Override void initialize()   { System.out.println("Football Game Initialized"); }
    @Override void startPlay()    { System.out.println("Football Game Started"); }
    @Override void endPlay()      { System.out.println("Football Game Finished"); }
}

public class TemplateDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Game g = new Cricket();
        g.play();
        System.out.println();
        g = new Football();
        g.play();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Cricket Game Initialized
Cricket Game Started
Cricket Game Finished

Football Game Initialized
Football Game Started
Football Game Finished
```

> [!TIP]
> **Why is `play()` declared `final`?** To prevent subclasses from changing the algorithm's skeleton (the order of method calls). This is the **defining feature** of the Template Method Pattern.

---

## 3.4 Analytical Matrix: When to Use Each Construct

| Scenario | Recommended Construct | Reasoning |
|---|---|---|
| Subclasses share code AND have a contract. | **Abstract Class** | Code reuse via concrete methods + enforced contract. |
| Subclasses share only a contract. | **Interface** | Pure abstraction; no shared state/code. |
| Need to inherit from multiple sources. | **Interface** | Java does not support multiple class inheritance. |
| Need a base class with constructors and state. | **Abstract Class** | Interfaces cannot have state. |
| Want to prevent instantiation of a utility class. | **Abstract Class with 0 abstract methods** | e.g., `abstract class MathUtils { ... }` |
| Need a default algorithm skeleton. | **Abstract Class with Template Method** | `final` template + `abstract` primitives. |

---

## 3.5 Derivation-Style Logical Proof: Why Abstract Classes Cannot Be `final`

Let us derive the contradiction formally:

$$C \rightarrow \text{class declared as final}$$

By the Java Language Specification, a `final` class **cannot be extended** by any subclass.

$$A \rightarrow \text{class declared as abstract}$$

An abstract class, by definition, **must be extended** so that its abstract methods can be implemented.

$$
\therefore \quad C \cap A = \emptyset
$$

**Conclusion:** Declaring a class as both `abstract` and `final` produces a logical contradiction тАФ the class can neither be instantiated (because it is abstract) nor extended (because it is final), leaving it permanently unusable. Hence Java's compiler rejects this combination.

The same logical argument extends to abstract methods:
- `abstract` mandates overriding.
- `static`, `final`, `private` forbid overriding.
- Hence these modifiers are mutually exclusive with `abstract`.

