#### Model Solution for Question B(b)

**Complete Java Program with Polymorphic Array:**

```java
// Abstract superclass
abstract class Vehicle {
    abstract int speed();   // contract: subclasses provide max speed
}

// Concrete subclass: Car
class Car extends Vehicle {
    @Override
    int speed() {
        return 220;        // km/h
    }
}

// Concrete subclass: Bike
class Bike extends Vehicle {
    @Override
    int speed() {
        return 120;        // km/h
    }
}

public class VehicleDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // POLYMORPHIC ARRAY тАФ array of superclass references
        Vehicle[] vehicles = new Vehicle[3];
        vehicles[0] = new Car();
        vehicles[1] = new Bike();
        vehicles[2] = new Car();

        // Dynamic method dispatch through the array
        for (int i = 0; i < vehicles.length; i++) {
            System.out.println("Vehicle " + (i+1) + " speed: " + vehicles[i].speed() + " km/h");
        }
    }
}
```

**Expected Output:**
```
Vehicle 1 speed: 220 km/h
Vehicle 2 speed: 120 km/h
Vehicle 3 speed: 220 km/h
```

**Explanation of Polymorphic Array Mechanism:**
- The array type is `Vehicle[]`, but it holds objects of `Car` and `Bike`.
- When `vehicles[i].speed()` is called, the JVM looks at the *actual runtime type* of the object and invokes the correct overridden method.
- This is **dynamic method dispatch** тАФ the cornerstone of runtime polymorphism in Java.

