# ЁЯУШ Section 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Standard)

> [!NOTE]
> **Interface (Java)** тАФ A reference type in Java, similar to a class, that can contain **only constants**, **method signatures (abstract methods)**, **default methods**, **static methods**, and **nested types**. It cannot be instantiated; it must be **implemented** by a class (using the `implements` keyword) or **extended** by another interface (using the `extends` keyword).

In the KTU 2024 Scheme syllabus, an **interface** is formally defined as a **pure abstract specification** that establishes a **contract** between the interface designer and the implementing class. Any concrete class that signs this contract guarantees to provide implementations for **all declared abstract methods** (unless the class itself is declared `abstract`).

### ЁЯза Conceptual Analogy тАФ The "Socket & Plug" Model

Think of an **interface as a universal power socket** on a wall:

- The **socket** (interface) defines a **standard shape** тАФ it has 3 holes, a specific voltage rating, and a ground pin.
- The **plug** (implementing class) must match that exact shape to function.
- The **wall** (Java runtime / JVM) doesn't care *who* manufactured the plug (which class), only that the **shape contract is satisfied**.

This means you can swap a Samsung plug for an LG plug (different classes), and the socket still works. The user writes code that depends on the **interface**, not the concrete class тАФ enabling **loose coupling**, **polymorphism**, and **plug-and-play** architecture.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Key Distinction** тАФ Unlike abstract classes, Java interfaces (prior to Java 8) were **100% abstract**. From **Java 8 onwards**, interfaces can have `default` and `static` methods with a body, but **state (instance variables)** is still forbidden (only `public static final` constants are allowed).

### 1.2 Purpose of Interfaces in OOP

| Engineering Goal | How Interface Achieves It |
|---|---|
| **Abstraction** | Hides implementation, shows only behavior contract |
| **Multiple Inheritance** | A class can implement **multiple** interfaces |
| **Loose Coupling** | Client code depends on interface, not concrete class |
| **Polymorphism** | One interface, many implementations (dynamic dispatch) |
| **Standardization** | Forces a uniform API across unrelated classes |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Board Tip** тАФ When asked "What is an interface?" in the 3-mark questions, always mention: **(i) blueprint/contract, (ii) cannot be instantiated, (iii) all methods abstract by default (pre-Java 8), (iv) used for multiple inheritance**, and **(v) supports polymorphism**.

### 1.3 Interface vs Class тАФ Quick Comparison

| Feature | Class | Interface (Java 7) | Interface (Java 8+) |
|---|---|---|---|
| `new InterfaceName()` | тЬЕ Allowed | тЭМ Not allowed | тЭМ Not allowed |
| Instance variables | тЬЕ Yes | тЭМ No (only `public static final`) | тЭМ No (only `public static final`) |
| Method body | тЬЕ Yes | тЭМ All abstract | тЬЕ Abstract + default + static |
| Constructor | тЬЕ Yes | тЭМ No | тЭМ No |
| Access modifiers for methods | public, protected, private, package-private | Implicitly `public abstract` | `public abstract`, `public default`, `public static` |
| Inheritance keyword | `extends` (single) | `implements` (multiple) | `implements` (multiple) |
| Can extend another interface? | N/A | `extends` (multiple allowed) | `extends` (multiple allowed) |

