# ЁЯУЧ Section 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 Anatomy of a Java Interface тАФ The Structural Rules

### ЁЯФ╣ Declaration Syntax

```java
[access_modifier] interface InterfaceName [extends ParentInterface1, ParentInterface2, ...] {
    // 1. Constant fields (implicitly public static final)
    // 2. Abstract method signatures (implicitly public abstract)
    // 3. Default methods (Java 8+) тАФ have a body
    // 4. Static methods (Java 8+) тАФ have a body, called via InterfaceName
    // 5. Nested types (classes or interfaces)
}
```

### ЁЯФ╣ The Five Pillars of Interface Members

1. **Constants** тАФ Every field is **implicitly** `public`, `static`, and `final`. You may write the modifiers explicitly, but they are redundant.

$$
\text{Interface Field} \equiv \texttt{public static final} \; \text{(always, implicitly)}
$$

2. **Abstract Methods** тАФ Every method without a body is **implicitly** `public` and `abstract`.

3. **Default Methods** (Java 8+) тАФ Declared with the `default` keyword, contain a body. Used for **backward-compatible evolution** of interfaces.

4. **Static Methods** (Java 8+) тАФ Declared with the `static` keyword, belong to the interface itself (not to instances). Called as `InterfaceName.method()`.

5. **Nested Types** тАФ An interface can contain a `class` or another `interface` (rarely used in KTU exams).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Hot Topic** тАФ A common 7-mark question asks: *"Explain default methods in interfaces with an example."* You MUST cover: **why introduced (backward compatibility)**, **how defined**, **how inherited/overridden**, and **the diamond problem resolution rule** (class wins over interface; more specific interface wins).

## 2.2 The "Why" Behind Each Rule тАФ Deep Reasoning

| Rule | Why It Exists (The Engineering Reason) |
|---|---|
| All fields `public static final` | Interfaces describe **behavior**, not state. Final prevents ambiguity when multiple interfaces declare the same constant. |
| All methods `public abstract` (pre-Java 8) | An interface is a **pure contract** тАФ the *what*, not the *how*. |
| Cannot be instantiated | No implementation exists for abstract methods, so creating an object is meaningless. |
| A class can implement **multiple** interfaces | Java forbids multiple class inheritance (due to the **Diamond Problem**), but multiple interface implementation is safe because interfaces (in the abstract-method sense) carry no state. |
| `extends` between interfaces is multiple | Interface A can extend B, C, D тАФ the child interface inherits **all** abstract signatures. |

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

> [!NOTE]
> The table below is the **golden reference** for the KTU board exam on this topic. Memorize the right column thoroughly.

| Concept | Formal Rule | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Implicit field modifiers | `public static final` | `int MAX = 100;` тЙб `public static final int MAX = 100;` |
| Implicit method modifiers (pre-Java 8) | `public abstract` | `void draw();` тЙб `public abstract void draw();` |
| Class implementing interface | `class C implements I` | `class Dog implements Animal` |
| Class implementing multiple interfaces | `class C implements I1, I2` | `class SmartPhone implements Camera, Phone` |
| Interface extending interface | `interface I2 extends I1` | `interface V8Engine extends Engine` |
| Interface extending multiple | `interface I3 extends I1, I2` | `interface FlyingCar extends Car, Aircraft` |
| Diamond Problem rule | **Class wins** over interface; if two interfaces conflict, the **most specific** (sub-interface) wins | See Section 3.4 |
| Cannot instantiate | `new I()` тЖТ **Compile Error** | `Animal a = new Animal(); // тЭМ` |
| Polymorphic reference | `I ref = new ImplementingClass();` тЬЕ | `Drawable d = new Circle();` |

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **JDBC API** тАФ `java.sql.Connection`, `Statement`, `ResultSet` are interfaces. Vendor drivers (MySQL, Oracle) provide implementations.
- **Collections Framework** тАФ `List`, `Map`, `Set` are interfaces. `ArrayList`, `HashMap`, `HashSet` are implementations.
- **Callback/Listener Pattern** тАФ GUI event handlers (`ActionListener`, `MouseListener`) are interfaces.
- **Strategy Design Pattern** тАФ Algorithms are encapsulated as interface implementations, swappable at runtime.
- **Dependency Injection (Spring Framework)** тАФ Beans are wired by interface, not by concrete class тАФ enabling testability and modularity.

