# ЁЯУЩ Section 3: Step-by-Step Analytical Walkthroughs & Code Derivations

## 3.1 Worked Example 1 тАФ Declaring and Implementing a Simple Interface

### Step 1: Declare the interface (the contract)

```java
// File: Drawable.java
public interface Drawable {
    // Implicitly public static final
    String TOOL = "Pen";

    // Implicitly public abstract
    void draw();
    double getArea();
}
```

**Explanation of each line:**
- `public interface Drawable` тАФ defines a public contract named `Drawable`.
- `String TOOL = "Pen";` тАФ a constant. The compiler automatically inserts `public static final`.
- `void draw();` тАФ an abstract method. The compiler inserts `public abstract`.
- `double getArea();` тАФ another abstract method.

### Step 2: Implement the interface in a concrete class

```java
// File: Circle.java
public class Circle implements Drawable {
    private double radius;

    public Circle(double radius) {
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a circle using " + TOOL);
    }

    @Override
    public double getArea() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }
}
```

### Step 3: Use polymorphic reference

```java
// File: MainApp.java
public class MainApp {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Interface reference тЖТ concrete object (upcasting)
        Drawable d = new Circle(5.0);
        d.draw();                  // Output: Drawing a circle using Pen
        System.out.println(d.getArea()); // Output: 78.5398...

        // Direct access to constant via interface name
        System.out.println(Drawable.TOOL); // Output: Pen
    }
}
```

**Key derivation flow:**

$$
\text{Interface Reference} \xrightarrow{\text{points to}} \text{Concrete Object}
$$

$$
\Rightarrow \text{Call resolved at runtime (Dynamic Method Dispatch)}
$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 14-Mark Favorite Question** тАФ "Write a Java program to define an interface `Shape` with methods `area()` and `perimeter()`. Implement it for `Rectangle` and `Circle`. Demonstrate polymorphism using an array of `Shape` references."

## 3.2 Worked Example 2 тАФ Multiple Interface Implementation (Resolving the Diamond Problem in Java)

```java
interface Printer {
    default void show() {
        System.out.println("Printer default show()");
    }
}

interface Scanner {
    default void show() {
        System.out.println("Scanner default show()");
    }
}

// Diamond Problem: which show() to inherit?
class AllInOneMachine implements Printer, Scanner {
    // MUST override to resolve ambiguity
    @Override
    public void show() {
        // Can explicitly call a specific interface's default
        Printer.super.show();
        System.out.println("AllInOneMachine's own show()");
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Resolution Logic

1. **Class inherits from two interfaces**, both declaring a `default` method with the **same signature** `show()`.
2. **Java compiler** throws an error: *"inherits unrelated defaults for show() from types Printer and Scanner"*.
3. **Solution**: The implementing class **must override** the conflicting method and may explicitly invoke a parent's version using the syntax `InterfaceName.super.methodName()`.

### General Rule Hierarchy (KTU Board Favorite)

$$
\text{Resolution Order:} \quad \text{(1) Class method} \; > \; \text{(2) Most specific sub-interface} \; > \; \text{(3) Compile Error (must override)}
$$

**Derivation of the formula:**

$$
\text{If } I_3 \text{ extends } I_1 \text{ and } I_2, \text{ then } I_3 \text{'s default wins over } I_1 \text{ and } I_2.
$$

$$
\text{If } I_1 \text{ and } I_2 \text{ are unrelated and both provide the same default, the implementing class MUST override.}
$$

## 3.3 Worked Example 3 тАФ Interface Inheritance (extends between interfaces)

```java
interface Vehicle {
    void start();
    void stop();
}

interface Car extends Vehicle {
    void honk();
    // Inherits start() and stop() from Vehicle
}

class Sedan implements Car {
    public void start() { System.out.println("Sedan started"); }
    public void stop()  { System.out.println("Sedan stopped"); }
    public void honk()  { System.out.println("Beep beep!"); }
}
```

**Derivation chain:**

$$
\text{Vehicle} \xrightarrow{\text{extends}} \text{Car} \xrightarrow{\text{implemented by}} \text{Sedan}
$$

Therefore, `Sedan` must implement **all three** abstract methods: `start()`, `stop()`, `honk()`.

## 3.4 Worked Example 4 тАФ Static Methods in Interfaces (Java 8+)

```java
interface MathUtils {
    static int square(int n) {
        return n * n;
    }

    // Cannot be overridden in implementing class as 'static' тАФ 
    // it is hidden, not overridden
    default int cube(int n) {
        return n * n * n;
    }
}

class Calculator implements MathUtils {
    // square() is NOT inherited тАФ it belongs to the interface
    // cube() IS inherited and CAN be overridden
}
```

**Calling convention:**

$$
\text{Static method:} \quad \texttt{MathUtils.square(5)} \quad \text{(called on interface, not on object)}
$$

$$
\text{Default method:} \quad \texttt{new Calculator().cube(5)} \quad \text{(called on object)}
$$

> [!WARNING]
> **Common KTU Mistake** тАФ Students often try to call `obj.square(5)` on a `Calculator` object. This is a **compile-time error** because `static` methods in interfaces are **not inherited** by implementing classes. They must be invoked using the interface name.

## 3.5 Worked Example 5 тАФ Functional Interfaces & Lambda Expressions (Java 8+)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Frequently Asked** тАФ A functional interface has **exactly one abstract method** and can be implemented using a **lambda expression**.

```java
@FunctionalInterface
interface Greeting {
    void sayHello(String name);
}

public class LambdaDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Lambda implementation
        Greeting g = (name) -> System.out.println("Hello, " + name + "!");
        g.sayHello("KTU Student");
    }
}
```

**Step-by-step derivation:**

$$
\text{Greeting interface (1 abstract method)} \;\xrightarrow{\text{lambda}}\; (name) \to \text{...}
$$

The compiler infers: the single abstract method `sayHello(String)` is being implemented by the lambda body. The `@FunctionalInterface` annotation is optional but **enforces** the single-abstract-method rule at compile time.

