**Diamond Problem Explanation (2 marks within Part b):**

The **diamond problem** occurs when a class inherits from **two interfaces** that both declare a `default` method with the **same signature**.

```java
interface A { default void hello() { System.out.println("A"); } }
interface B { default void hello() { System.out.println("B"); } }

// class C implements A, B   //  COMPILE ERROR
```

**Java's Resolution Rule (3-tier):**

1. **Class implementation wins** тАФ If the class `C` provides its own `hello()`, that overrides everything.
2. **Most specific sub-interface wins** тАФ If `interface B extends A` and both define `hello()`, then `B`'s version wins.
3. **Compile-time error** тАФ If neither rule resolves it, the implementing class **must explicitly override** the method or the code will not compile.

```java
class C implements A, B {
    @Override
    public void hello() {
        A.super.hello();   // explicit call to A's version
        System.out.println("C's own logic");
    }
}
```

