> 1. **Forgetting `@Override` annotation** тАФ While not a syntax error, KTU examiners deduct ┬╜ mark for not using it. Always annotate interface implementations.
> 2. **Writing `public` redundantly inside an interface** тАФ It is *not* wrong, but writing modifiers explicitly when the compiler inserts them implicitly is considered a waste of answer space. Use this only if the question asks "explain implicit modifiers."
> 3. **Confusing `extends` and `implements`** тАФ A class `extends` another class; a class `implements` an interface. An interface `extends` another interface. Mixing these is a **favourite trap** in the 7-mark questions.
> 4. **Trying to instantiate an interface** тАФ `Drawable d = new Drawable();` is a compile error. The KTU examiner will instantly deduct 1 mark.
> 5. **Missing the `default` keyword** in Java 8 questions тАФ Writing `void fuelType() { ... }` inside an interface (without `default` or `static`) is a **compile error** in Java 7 but valid in Java 8+ only with the `default` keyword. KTU specifically tests this.
> 6. **Not explaining the "why"** тАФ A 14-mark question expects both **code (10 marks)** and **conceptual reasoning (4 marks)**. Writing only code without explaining polymorphism, loose coupling, or the diamond problem leads to a 2-3 mark deduction.
