# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The Two Mandatory Rules of Checked Exceptions

The Java compiler enforces **two mandatory rules** for checked exceptions:

### Rule 1: The "Handle or Declare" Rule

For every checked exception that a method can throw, the method MUST do **one** of the following:

$$
\text{Checked Exception Handling} = \begin{cases} \text{Option A: Wrap risky code inside a try-catch block} \\ \text{Option B: Declare in method signature using throws clause} \\ \text{Violation: Compilation Error (UNREPORTED EXCEPTION)} \end{cases}
$$

### Rule 2: The Override Restriction Rule

When a subclass overrides a method from a superclass:

$$
\text{Overriding Rule} \Rightarrow \text{Subclass method can throw} \begin{cases} \text{Fewer checked exceptions} \\ \text{No checked exceptions} \\ \text{Narrower/same checked exceptions as parent} \end{cases}
$$

The subclass **cannot throw new or broader checked exceptions** than the parent method declares.

---

## 2.2 Mechanism Breakdown тАФ How Checked Exceptions Work

The compiler performs the following logical sequence:

- **Step 1 тАФ Method Body Analysis:** The compiler statically scans the method body for statements that may throw checked exceptions (e.g., `new FileReader("a.txt")` which can throw `FileNotFoundException`).
- **Step 2 тАФ Exception Identification:** For each risky statement, the compiler identifies the declared checked exception type from the method's signature in the API.
- **Step 3 тАФ Verification Phase:** The compiler checks if the current method:
  - Contains a `try-catch` block that catches **the exact type** or a **superclass** of the exception, OR
  - Declares the exception (or its superclass) in its `throws` clause.
- **Step 4 тАФ Decision:** If neither condition is satisfied тЖТ **Compile-Time Error: "unreported exception XxxException; must be caught or declared to be thrown"**.
- **Step 5 тАФ Propagation:** If declared with `throws`, the exception propagates up the call stack until a calling method either handles it or itself declares it (recursively up to `main()` or the JVM).

---

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

