## 2.4 The `throws` vs `throw` Distinction (HIGH-YIELD)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU students frequently confuse `throw` and `throws`. Memorize this:**

| Keyword | Purpose | Location | Used With |
|---|---|---|---|
| `throw` | **Actually throws** an exception object | Inside method body | An exception instance (e.g., `throw new IOException()`) |
| `throws` | **Declares** possible exceptions | Method signature (after parameters) | Exception class names (e.g., `throws IOException`) |

$$
\text{throw} = \text{ACTION (do it now)} \quad | \quad \text{throws} = \text{DECLARATION (announce possibility)}
$$

---

## 2.5 Real-World Utility of Checked Exceptions in Engineering

- **Enterprise File Processing Systems:** Java's `java.io` and `java.nio` APIs use checked exceptions to force developers to handle disk failures, missing files, and read/write errors. This prevents silent data corruption in banking and healthcare software.
- **Database Applications (JDBC):** `SQLException` is checked because database operations (network drops, deadlocks, constraint violations) are *predictable but recoverable*. Forcing explicit handling prevents transactions from silently failing.
- **Network Programming:** `java.net.Socket`, `URL` classes throw checked exceptions (`MalformedURLException`, `IOException`) to ensure engineers design retry and fallback logic тАФ critical for distributed systems.
- **Robustness in Critical Systems:** Checked exceptions embody the "fail-fast, handle-explicitly" philosophy, which is mandated by safety standards like **DO-178C (aviation)** and **IEC 62304 (medical devices)**.
