# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Analytical Matrix тАФ Decision Logic for Handling a Checked Exception

When a programmer writes a method containing a risky operation, the following **decision tree** is mentally evaluated:

$$
\text{Decision Flow} \Rightarrow
\begin{aligned}
&\textbf{Step 1:} \text{ Identify the method-call that may throw a checked exception.} \\
&\textbf{Step 2:} \text{ Read the API to determine the exception type (e.g., FileNotFoundException).} \\
&\textbf{Step 3:} \text{ Ask: "Is the method-level responsibility to fix this?"} \\
&\quad \bullet \text{ If YES} \rightarrow \text{Handle locally with try-catch (Option A).} \\
&\quad \bullet \text{ If NO} \rightarrow \text{Declare with throws (Option B) and let caller decide.} \\
&\textbf{Step 4:} \text{ If declaring тАФ list the exception (or its parent) in throws clause.} \\
&\textbf{Step 5:} \text{ Propagate upward until some caller chooses Option A or JVM terminates.}
\end{aligned}
$$

---

## 3.2 Step-by-Step Demonstration: How the Compiler Catches a Violation

Let's trace through what the compiler does with this **invalid** code:

```java
import java.io.*;
class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        FileReader fr = new FileReader("data.txt");  // LINE A
    }
}
```

### Compiler's Logical Evaluation:

$$
\text{Evaluation at LINE A} \Rightarrow
\begin{aligned}
&\textbf{Step 1:} \text{ The constructor } FileReader(\text{String filename}) \text{ is documented as} \\
&\quad \text{throwing } \textbf{FileNotFoundException} \text{ (a checked exception).} \\
&\textbf{Step 2:} \text{ The compiler checks: Is LINE A inside a try-catch block?} \\
&\quad \text{Answer: NO.} \\
&\textbf{Step 3:} \text{ The compiler checks: Does main() declare this exception in its throws clause?} \\
&\quad \text{Answer: NO тАФ current signature is } \texttt{public static void main(String[] args)}. \\
&\textbf{Step 4:} \text{ Compiler concludes: "Unhandled checked exception тАФ UNREPORTED EXCEPTION."} \\
&\textbf{Step 5:} \text{ Compilation is ABORTED with error:}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\boxed{\texttt{error: unreported exception FileNotFoundException; must be caught or declared to be thrown}}
$$

### Corrected Versions (Two Valid Fixes):

**Fix Option A тАФ Handle Locally:**

```java
import java.io.*;
class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            FileReader fr = new FileReader("data.txt");
        } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
            System.out.println("File not found: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Fix Option B тАФ Declare with throws:**

```java
import java.io.*;
class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws FileNotFoundException {
        FileReader fr = new FileReader("data.txt");
    }
}
```

---

## 3.3 Analytical Proof: The Override Restriction Rule

**Theorem:** A subclass overriding method can throw *only* checked exceptions that are subclasses (or the same) of those declared by the parent method.

### Logical Proof by Example:

```java
class Parent {
    void readFile() throws IOException {           // declares IOException
        // ...
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    @Override
    void readFile() throws FileNotFoundException { // ALLOWED тАФ narrower
        // ...
    }
}
```

$$
\text{Validity Check} \Rightarrow
\begin{aligned}
&\textbf{Parent declares:} \ IOException \\
&\textbf{Child declares:} \ FileNotFoundException \\
&\text{Is } FileNotFoundException \text{ a subclass of } IOException? \\
&\text{Yes } (\texttt{FileNotFoundException extends IOException}). \\
&\therefore \text{ This override is VALID (narrower or equal checked exceptions).}
\end{aligned}
$$

### Counter-Example (INVALID Override):

```java
class Child2 extends Parent {
    @Override
    void readFile() throws Exception {  // INVALID тАФ broader than IOException
        // ...
    }
}
```

$$
\text{Invalidity Proof} \Rightarrow
\begin{aligned}
&\text{Is } Exception \text{ a subclass of } IOException? \\
&\text{NO тАФ in fact, } IOException \text{ is a subclass of } Exception. \\
&\text{Therefore } Exception \text{ is BROADER (parent) of } IOException. \\
&\therefore \text{ Override VIOLATES the rule тЖТ Compile Error.}
\end{aligned}
$$

### General Rule (Exam-Ready Formula):

$$
\boxed{
\forall \text{ checked exception } E_c \text{ thrown by subclass method}, \\
E_c \text{ must be a subclass of (or equal to) } E_p \text{ thrown by parent method}
}
$$

---

## 3.4 Custom Checked Exception тАФ Complete Construction Analysis

To create a custom checked exception, we **extend `Exception`** (not `RuntimeException`):

```java
class InsufficientBalanceException extends Exception {
    private double balance;
    private double amount;

    public InsufficientBalanceException(double balance, double amount) {
        super("Insufficient balance: " + balance + ", tried to withdraw: " + amount);
        this.balance = balance;
        this.amount = amount;
    }

    public double getBalance()   { return balance; }
    public double getAmount()    { return amount; }
}
```

### Usage Analysis:

```java
class BankAccount {
    private double balance = 500;

    public void withdraw(double amount) throws InsufficientBalanceException {
        if (amount > balance) {
            throw new InsufficientBalanceException(balance, amount);
        }
        balance -= amount;
    }
}
```

### Caller-side Decision Matrix:

$$
\text{Caller Logic} \Rightarrow
\begin{aligned}
&\textbf{Step 1:} \text{ Caller invokes } \texttt{withdraw(1000)}. \\
&\textbf{Step 2:} \text{ Since } InsufficientBalanceException \text{ is checked, caller MUST} \\
&\quad \text{either catch it or re-declare it.} \\
&\textbf{Step 3:} \text{ If caller chooses to catch:}
\end{aligned}
$$

```java
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccount acc = new BankAccount();
        try {
            acc.withdraw(1000);
        } catch (InsufficientBalanceException e) {
            System.out.println("Caught: " + e.getMessage());
            System.out.println("Current Balance: " + e.getBalance());
        }
    }
}
```

$$
\text{Result:} \rightarrow \texttt{"Caught: Insufficient balance: 500.0, tried to withdraw: 1000.0"}
$$

---

## 3.5 Try-With-Resources Derivation (Java 7+ Feature)

For resources implementing `AutoCloseable`, Java 7 introduced automatic resource management.

### Before Java 7 (Verbose):

```java
FileReader fr = null;
try {
    fr = new FileReader("data.txt");
    // use fr
} catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
    e.printStackTrace();
} finally {
    if (fr != null) {
        try { fr.close(); } catch (IOException e) { /* swallow */ }
    }
}
```

### After Java 7 (Concise тАФ KTU Preferred Form):

```java
try (FileReader fr = new FileReader("data.txt")) {
    // use fr
    int ch;
    while ((ch = fr.read()) != -1) {
        System.out.print((char) ch);
    }
} catch (IOException e) {
    e.printStackTrace();
}
```

$$
\text{Key Insight} \Rightarrow \text{The resource } fr \text{ is automatically closed at the end of the try block,} \\
\text{even if an exception occurs. The } fr.close() \text{ is implicitly called by the compiler.}
$$

---

## 3.6 Multi-Catch Clause Derivation

Instead of writing multiple catch blocks for unrelated exceptions, Java 7+ allows:

```java
try {
    // risky code that may throw IOException OR SQLException
} catch (IOException | SQLException e) {
    System.out.println("Database or I/O issue: " + e.getMessage());
}
```

$$
\text{Compiler Restriction} \Rightarrow \text{The exceptions in a multi-catch clause must NOT have an} \\
\text{inheritance relationship (no parent-child relationship allowed).} \\
\text{For example: } \texttt{catch (IOException | FileNotFoundException e)} \rightarrow \textbf{COMPILE ERROR}
$$

---

## 3.7 Method Overriding with Checked Exceptions тАФ Complete Truth Table

| Parent Method Signature | Valid Child Override | Invalid Child Override |
|---|---|---|
| `void m() throws IOException` | `void m() throws FileNotFoundException` | `void m() throws Exception` |
| `void m() throws IOException` | `void m() throws IOException` | `void m() throws SQLException` |
| `void m() throws IOException` | `void m()` (no throws) | `void m() throws IOException, SQLException` |
| `void m()` (no throws) | `void m()` (no throws) | `void m() throws IOException` |
| `void m() throws A, B` | `void m() throws A` | `void m() throws C` (unrelated new exception) |

$$
\boxed{\text{Memory Aid: "Child can SHRINK the throws list, but NEVER EXPAND it."}}
$$
