# SECTION 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1: `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`
**Define checked exception in Java. Give two examples.**

**Model Answer:**

A checked exception in Java is an exception that is **verified at compile-time** by the Java compiler. The compiler ensures that every method which can produce such an exception either **handles it** using a `try-catch` block or **declares it** in its method signature using the `throws` keyword. Checked exceptions extend `java.lang.Exception` directly but do **not** extend `java.lang.RuntimeException`.

**Two Examples:**
1. **`IOException`** тАФ Thrown when an input/output operation fails or is interrupted (e.g., file reading errors).
2. **`FileNotFoundException`** тАФ Thrown when attempting to open a file at a path that does not exist. *(Also acceptable: `SQLException`, `ClassNotFoundException`, `CloneNotSupportedException`.)*

---

### Question 2: `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`
**Differentiate between `throw` and `throws` keywords in Java.**

**Model Answer:**

| Aspect | `throw` | `throws` |
|---|---|---|
| **Purpose** | Used to explicitly throw an exception object | Used to declare exceptions a method might throw |
| **Location** | Inside the method body | In the method signature (after parameters) |
| **Syntax** | `throw new IOException("msg");` | `void read() throws IOException { }` |
| **Number of Exceptions** | Throws only **one** exception at a time | Can declare **multiple** exceptions separated by commas |
| **Followed by** | An exception **instance** | An exception **class name** |

**Memory Aid:** *throw = action; throws = announcement.*

