### QUESTION A (14 Marks) тАФ `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**(a) [7 Marks]** Explain the hierarchy of exception classes in Java with a neat diagram. Distinguish between checked and unchecked exceptions.

**(b) [7 Marks]** Write a Java program that reads a filename from the user and displays its contents. Handle the appropriate checked exceptions.

#### Model Solution for (a):

The Java exception hierarchy has its root in `java.lang.Throwable`. It has two major subclasses:

1. **`java.lang.Exception`** тАФ Represents conditions that programs can reasonably recover from.
   - **Checked exceptions** (compile-time checked): `IOException`, `SQLException`, `ClassNotFoundException`, etc.
   - **Unchecked exceptions** (runtime): Subclasses of `RuntimeException` such as `ArithmeticException`, `NullPointerException`, `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException`.

2. **`java.lang.Error`** тАФ Represents severe, unrecoverable problems (e.g., `OutOfMemoryError`, `StackOverflowError`). Programs typically do not catch these.

**Diagram:**

```mermaid
graph TD
    A["Throwable"] --> B["Exception"]
    A --> C["Error"]
    B --> D["IOException (CHECKED)"]
    B --> E["SQLException (CHECKED)"]
    B --> F["RuntimeException (UNCHECKED)"]
    F --> G["ArithmeticException"]
    F --> H["NullPointerException"]
    C --> I["OutOfMemoryError"]
    C --> J["StackOverflowError"]
    style D fill:#FFD700
    style E fill:#FFD700
    style F fill:#87CEEB
```

**Distinction Table:**

| Feature | Checked Exception | Unchecked Exception |
|---|---|---|
| Superclass | `Exception` (not RuntimeException) | `RuntimeException` |
| Checked at | **Compile-time** | Runtime |
| Compiler enforcement | Must handle or declare | Optional handling |
| Examples | `IOException`, `SQLException` | `ArithmeticException`, `NullPointerException` |
| Recovery | Expected to be recoverable | Often programming bugs |

