## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistakes That Cost Marks in KTU Exams:**
>
> 1. **Confusing `throw` and `throws`:** Writing `throws new IOException()` instead of `throw new IOException()` тАФ instant zero for that sub-question. *Examiner's tip: `throw` is an action verb (do it now); `throws` is a declaration (announce).*
>
> 2. **Extending `RuntimeException` for custom checked exceptions:** A student writes `class MyEx extends RuntimeException` and expects it to be checked. **WRONG** тАФ anything extending `RuntimeException` is unchecked by definition.
>
> 3. **Forgetting to handle OR declare:** Leaving a `new FileReader()` call bare in `main()` without `try-catch` or `throws` results in compilation failure. The KTU examiner will deduct **all marks** if the program doesn't compile conceptually.
>
> 4. **Breaking the Override Rule:** Declaring `throws Exception` in a subclass method while the parent declares `throws IOException`. The examiner tests this with code snippets тАФ **marks deducted for any broader exception declaration.**
>
> 5. **Confusing Checked vs Unchecked Examples:** Writing `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` or `NullPointerException` as examples of checked exceptions. These are **unchecked** тАФ instant loss of 1-2 marks.
>
> 6. **Not mentioning the "compile-time" aspect:** A definition that omits the **compile-time verification** nature of checked exceptions is considered incomplete. Always mention this in your answer.

