# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Operational Mechanics of `throw` тАФ Step-by-Step Logic

When the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) encounters a `throw` statement, the following structured sequence is executed **atomically**:

1. **Evaluation Phase:** The expression on the right-hand side of `throw` is fully evaluated. This **must** produce a non-null reference to a `Throwable` (or subclass) object. If it is `null`, a `NullPointerException` is thrown **instead** by the JVM.
2. **Object Instantiation:** Typically the expression is `new SomeException("message")`, which invokes the constructor of the exception class and stores diagnostic information (stack trace, message, cause).
3. **Stack-Unwind Initiation:** The JVM **aborts normal sequential execution** at the point of `throw`. All code after the `throw` statement inside the same block becomes **unreachable** (the compiler will actually flag this with "unreachable code" error).
4. **Catch-Search Phase:** The JVM inspects the current method. If the method is **enclosed in a `try` block** with a `catch` clause whose parameter type is `Throwable` or a superclass of the thrown object, control jumps to that `catch` block.
5. **Propagation Phase:** If no enclosing `try-catch` is found in the current method, the current method **terminates abnormally** and the exception is **propagated** to the caller. The process repeats up the call stack.
6. **Default Handler:** If the call stack is exhausted without a handler, the JVM's **default uncaught exception handler** prints the stack trace to `System.err` and terminates the program with a non-zero exit code.

> [!NOTE]
> **Why "the nearest" `catch`?** Java uses **dynamic nearest-match** semantics, not lexical. The `catch` chosen is the **first one encountered during stack unwinding** whose declared parameter is the same type as, or a supertype of, the thrown object. Once caught, propagation stops.

---

## 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

The following table consolidates every key rule, syntax constraint, and behavioural guarantee of the `throw` keyword required for KTU 2024 ESE answers.

| **#** | **Rule / Property** | **Specification** | **Example / Note** |
|:-:|---|---|---|
| 1 | Syntax | `throw <ThrowableRef>;` | `throw new IOException("disk full");` |
| 2 | Operand type | Must be `Throwable` or subclass | `throw new MyException();` |
| 3 | Operand count | **Exactly one** per statement | `throw e;` (rethrow) |
| 4 | Position | Method body, constructor, initializer | Cannot appear at class level |
| 5 | Checked exception usage | Must be **declared** in enclosing `throws` clause OR wrapped in `try-catch` | `static void m() throws IOException { throw new IOException(); }` |
| 6 | Unchecked exception usage | No declaration or catch **required** | `throw new ArithmeticException();` |
| 7 | Custom exception | Class must extend `Exception` (checked) or `RuntimeException` (unchecked) | `class MyEx extends Exception { тАж }` |
| 8 | Re-throwing | Use `throw ex;` inside a `catch` block | Preserves stack trace (or not, if `ex.fillInStackTrace()` is altered) |
| 9 | Unreachable code | Lines after `throw` in same block | Compiler **error**: "unreachable statement" |
| 10 | Null operand | `throw null;` yields `NullPointerException` at runtime | Pitfall тАФ never throw `null` |
| 11 | Chaining | `throw new Exception("cause", originalEx);` | Preserves the **cause chain** |
| 12 | Exit method | Method **terminates immediately** | No `return` needed after `throw` |
| 13 | `final` block | **`finally` still executes** even after `throw` | Classic KTU question |
| 14 | `throw` vs `throws` | `throw` = one object, body; `throws` = declaration, signature | See Section 4 diagram |
| 15 | JLS Reference | Java Language Specification ┬з14.18 | Authoritative source |

