## 2.3 Real-World Engineering Utility

In professional Java applications (Spring Boot, Android, banking systems), the `throw` keyword is the **cornerstone of defensive programming**. Concrete engineering scenarios include:

- **Input validation in REST controllers** тАФ throwing `IllegalArgumentException` or custom `ValidationException` when client data is malformed.
- **Business-rule enforcement** тАФ e.g., in an e-commerce system, throwing `InsufficientStockException` when the requested quantity exceeds inventory.
- **Resource guards** тАФ throwing `IllegalStateException` if a method is called before proper initialization (`init()` was not invoked).
- **Authentication/Authorization** тАФ Spring Security internally throws `AccessDeniedException` using the same `throw` mechanism.
- **Pre-condition enforcement** тАФ `Objects.requireNonNull(obj, "obj must not be null");` internally executes `throw new NullPointerException(message);`.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Engineering Best Practice:** Throw exceptions **early** (fail-fast) and handle them **as close to the recovery logic as possible**. Never use `throw` for normal control flow тАФ exceptions are expensive (stack-trace capture costs CPU cycles).
