## 3.3 Derivation 3: Re-throwing an Exception (Exception Chaining & Re-throw Pattern)

```java
// File: ThrowDemo3.java
public class ThrowDemo3 {

    static void level1() throws Exception {
        System.out.println("level1(): about to throw");
        throw new Exception("Original failure in level1");
    }

    static void level2() throws Exception {
        try {
            level1();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("level2(): caught, adding context, rethrowing");
            // Re-throw preserves the original stack trace
            throw new Exception("Wrapped failure during level2 processing", e);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            level2();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("main(): " + e.getMessage());
            System.out.println("Cause: " + e.getCause().getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

### Output and Trace

```
level1(): about to throw
level2(): caught, adding context, rethrowing
main(): Wrapped failure during level2 processing
Cause: Original failure in level1
```

### Analytical Matrix тАФ Three Re-throw Variants

| **Variant** | **Code** | **Effect on Stack Trace** | **Use Case** |
|---|---|---|---|
| Plain re-throw | `throw e;` | Original stack trace **preserved** | Logging in middle layer, then propagating |
| Wrapped re-throw | `throw new Ex("ctx", e);` | New trace; original in `getCause()` | Adding business context (preferred) |
| Throwable-rethrow | `throw (Throwable) e;` | Forces `throws Throwable` declaration | Used for framework-level wrappers |

---

## 3.4 Derivation 4: Showing That Statements After `throw` Are Unreachable

```java
public class UnreachableDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        throw new RuntimeException("Boom!");
        // System.out.println("This will NEVER compile");
    }
}
```

The compiler issues:
```
error: unreachable statement
        System.out.println("This will NEVER compile");
```

**Mathematical/Logical Guarantee:**

$$
\forall \, s \in S_{\text{after}} : \text{InstructionCounter}(s) = \infty
$$

That is, every statement $s$ appearing lexically after a `throw` in the same basic block has **infinite** control-flow distance тАФ it can never be reached. The Java compiler formalizes this in JLS ┬з14.21.
