## 5.1 Part A Questions (2 Marks Each тАФ Short Answer)

### Question 1 (3 Marks)
**`[KTU University Exam тАУ Dec 2023, Module 3]`**

> **Q:** What is the purpose of the `throw` keyword in Java? Write its general syntax. Can a `throw` statement throw multiple exceptions at once? Justify.

**Model Answer:**

The `throw` keyword in Java is used to **explicitly raise (trigger) an exception** from within a method body, constructor, or initializer block. It is followed by a **single instance** of `java.lang.Throwable` (or any subclass), allowing the programmer to signal an abnormal condition and transfer control to the nearest enclosing `try-catch` block (or up the call stack if none exists).

**General syntax:**

```java
throw <ThrowableReference>;
```

**Multiple exceptions:** **No.** A `throw` statement can dispatch **only one** exception object per execution. Attempting to write `throw new A(), new B();` is a **compile-time error** in Java. If multiple exceptions must be signalled, they must be thrown sequentially in separate `throw` statements, or wrapped via exception chaining using the `(message, cause)` constructor.

---

### Question 2 (3 Marks)
**`[KTU University Exam тАУ May 2024, Module 3]`**

> **Q:** Differentiate between `throw` and `throws` in Java. Give one example of each.

**Model Answer:**

| **Feature** | **`throw`** | **`throws`** |
|---|---|---|
| Keyword type | Action (verb) тАФ actually raises an exception | Declaration (advisory) тАФ informs compiler |
| Location | Method body | Method signature (header) |
| Followed by | A **Throwable object reference** | A **comma-separated list of exception class names** |
| Number of exceptions | **One** per statement | **One or more** |
| Effect on control flow | Immediately transfers control | No transfer тАФ purely declarative |
| Compiler enforcement | None specific; checked exceptions need separate handling | Compiler **forces** caller to either `try-catch` or re-declare `throws` |

**Example of `throw`:**
```java
throw new ArithmeticException("/ by zero");
```

**Example of `throws`:**
```java
static void readFile() throws IOException, FileNotFoundException { тАж }
```

