# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference Sheet

## 2.1 Deep Dive into `throws`

### The `throws` Clause тАФ Rules and Logic

- **Checked Exceptions Only (mostly):** `throws` is typically used to declare **checked exceptions** (compile-time), such as `IOException`, `SQLException`, `ClassNotFoundException`. Unchecked exceptions (subclasses of `RuntimeException`) can also be declared, but it is optional.
- **Signature-Level Declaration:** The `throws` keyword appears **after the parameter list and before the method body**, separated by a single space.
- **Multiple Exceptions:** A method may declare multiple exception types separated by commas.
- **Propagation Chain:** Exceptions declared in `throws` are **propagated** up the call stack until a `try-catch` handles them or the JVM terminates the program.
- **Overriding Rule:** A subclass overriding a method can declare **same, fewer, or narrower** checked exceptions тАФ but never new or broader checked exceptions.
- **Constructors Can `throws` Too:** Constructors can use the `throws` clause just like methods, because they are special member functions.

### Why and How `throws` Works тАФ Step-by-Step Logic

1. The compiler checks the method body for any statement that may throw a checked exception.
2. If the method does not enclose the statement in a `try-catch`, the compiler **forces** the method to declare the exception using `throws`.
3. At runtime, if the exception occurs, the JVM creates an exception object and **unwinds** the call stack, looking for the nearest matching `catch` block.
4. If no matching `catch` is found in the entire call stack, the JVM's default exception handler prints the stack trace and terminates.

### Real-World Engineering Utility
The `throws` mechanism is the **bedrock of checked exception safety** in enterprise Java. It forces developers to **acknowledge failure paths** during API design. For example, when writing a file I/O utility, the API designer must communicate to the caller that the operation may fail due to disk errors, permission issues, or network timeouts.

---

## 2.2 Deep Dive into `finally`

### The `finally` Block тАФ Rules and Logic

- **Placement:** Appears after the last `catch` block (or directly after `try` if no `catch` is used).
- **Execution Guarantee:** Executes in **four** scenarios: (1) Normal flow, (2) Exception thrown and caught, (3) Exception thrown and **not** caught, (4) `return` statement in `try` or `catch`.
- **Resource Cleanup:** The **primary use case** is releasing system resources (file handles, sockets, database connections).
- **Try-with-Resources Alternative:** Since Java 7, `try-with-resources` (using `AutoCloseable`) is the preferred way to handle resources, replacing many uses of `finally`.
- **Cannot Have a `return` (best practice):** Although technically allowed, returning from `finally` is a **coding anti-pattern** that swallows exceptions.
- **System.exit() Escape Hatch:** The only way to skip `finally` is `System.exit(int)` or JVM crash.

### Why and How `finally` Works тАФ Step-by-Step Logic

1. When the `try` block begins execution, the JVM internally pushes a "try frame" onto the stack.
2. Upon exiting the `try` (or `catch`) block тАФ whether normally or via exception тАФ the JVM **always** transfers control to the `finally` block.
3. The `finally` block runs to completion.
4. After `finally` completes, control returns to the original exit point (caller), or the exception continues propagation if it was not caught.

### Real-World Engineering Utility
In production-grade systems, `finally` is used in:
- **Database connection pools** тАФ releasing connections back to the pool.
- **File I/O operations** тАФ closing file streams to prevent file descriptor leaks.
- **Network programming** тАФ closing sockets gracefully.
- **Transaction management** тАФ committing or rolling back based on success/failure.

---

## 2.3 Deep Dive into String Constructors

### Why Multiple Constructors Exist
Different data sources store text in different forms. The `String` class offers constructors to convert these heterogeneous sources into the canonical immutable `String` format.

### The KTU Reference Sheet тАФ String Constructors (Mandatory for 14-Mark Questions)

| **Constructor Signature** | **Purpose** | **Typical Use Case** |
|---|---|---|
| `String()` | Creates an **empty** String (`""`) | Default placeholder, initialization |
| `String(String original)` | **Copy** constructor тАФ creates a new String with identical content | Defensive copying, cloning |
| `String(char[] value)` | Converts a **full char array** to String | GUI text fields, low-level char buffers |
| `String(char[] value, int offset, int count)` | Converts a **subarray** of chars to String | Slicing a portion of a character buffer |
| `String(int[] codePoints, int offset, int count)` | Converts **Unicode code points** to String | Internationalization (i18n), Unicode handling |
| `String(byte[] bytes)` | Decodes bytes using **default platform charset** | Legacy byte stream data |
| `String(byte[] bytes, int offset, int length)` | Decodes a **subarray** of bytes (default charset) | Network packet fragments |
| `String(byte[] bytes, String charsetName)` | Decodes bytes using a **named charset** (e.g., "UTF-8") | Cross-platform I/O |
| `String(byte[] bytes, int offset, int length, String charsetName)` | Subarray with **named charset** | Precise byte-slice decoding |
| `String(byte[] bytes, Charset charset)` | Decodes bytes using a **Charset object** | Modern, type-safe charset specification |
| `String(byte[] bytes, int offset, int length, Charset charset)` | Subarray with **Charset object** | Full control over decoding |
| `String(StringBuffer buffer)` | Synchronized **mutable-to-immutable** conversion | Legacy multi-threaded string building |
| `String(StringBuilder builder)` | **Non-synchronized** mutable-to-immutable conversion | Modern single-threaded string building |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight:** The `String(byte[], Charset)` constructors (Java 1.6+) are the **recommended** way to handle byte-to-String conversion, as they avoid the platform-dependency issues of `String(byte[])` which uses the default charset (a notorious source of bugs in international software).

