## 4.1 Execution Flow Diagram тАФ `try-catch-finally`

The following Mermaid diagram illustrates the **runtime control flow** of a `try-catch-finally` construct across all possible execution paths.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    entryPoint(["Method Entry"]) --> tryStart{"Enter try block"}
    tryStart --> tryBody["Execute try body code"]
    tryBody --> exceptionCheck{"Exception thrown?"}
    exceptionCheck -->|No| normalExit["Normal completion of try"]
    exceptionCheck -->|Yes, checked or unchecked| catchCheck{"Matching catch block?"}
    catchCheck -->|Yes| catchBody["Execute catch handler"]
    catchCheck -->|No, propagates up| propagate["Exception propagates to caller"]
    normalExit --> finallyStart["Enter finally block"]
    catchBody --> finallyStart
    propagate --> finallyStart
    finallyStart --> finallyBody["Execute finally cleanup code"]
    finallyBody --> finallyExit["Exit finally"]
    finallyExit --> methodEnd(["Method returns / continues"])
    propagate --> jvmHandler["JVM prints stack trace, terminates program"]
```

**Reading the diagram:**
- The `finally` block is the **single convergence point** тАФ every path (normal, caught, uncaught) flows through it.
- The only escape from `finally` is the **JVM termination** path, triggered by `System.exit()` or fatal crashes.

