### **Question B (14 Marks)** `[KTU University Exam - May 2024 тАФ Alternative Module Choice]`

**(a)** Explain the `throws` clause in Java. Write a Java program that uses `throws` to propagate an `IOException` from a method to its caller. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Explain any eight constructors of the `String` class in Java with code examples. **(7 Marks)**

#### Model Solution:

**(a) The `throws` Clause тАФ Theory and Program (7 Marks):**

The `throws` keyword is used in a **method signature** to declare that the method may throw one or more checked exceptions. The caller of the method is then responsible for either handling the exception (with `try-catch`) or further declaring it using its own `throws` clause.

**Program:**
```java
import java.io.*;

class ThrowsExample {
    // Method declares it may throw IOException
    static void readFile(String filename) throws IOException {
        FileReader fr = new FileReader(filename);
        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(fr);
        System.out.println("First line: " + br.readLine());
        br.close();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            readFile("test.txt");
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("IOException caught in main: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**

- `readFile()` declares `throws IOException` because `FileReader` and `BufferedReader` are file I/O operations that can fail.
- The compiler **forces** `readFile()` to declare `throws` (or use try-catch) because `IOException` is checked.
- When `readFile()` is called inside `main`, the call must be wrapped in `try-catch` (or `main` must also declare `throws`).
- If `"test.txt"` does not exist, `FileNotFoundException` (a subclass of `IOException`) is thrown, propagating to `main`'s `catch` block.

---

**(b) String Constructors тАФ Detailed Explanation (7 Marks):**

```java
public class StringConstructors {
