# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Operational Breakdown тАФ How `suspend()` Worked

- **Step 1:** Thread `T` enters a `synchronized` block and acquires the intrinsic lock of object `O`.
- **Step 2:** Another thread calls `T.suspend()`.
- **Step 3:** The JVM marks `T` as a "Suspended" thread. `T` does **not** release lock `O`.
- **Step 4:** Thread `U` tries to enter a `synchronized` block on `O` тЖТ blocks indefinitely.
- **Step 5:** Only when `T.resume()` is called does `T` continue, eventually releasing the lock at block exit.

## 2.2 Operational Breakdown тАФ How `wait()`/`notify()` Works (Modern Alternative)

- **Step 1:** Thread `T` acquires intrinsic lock of object `O` via `synchronized`.
- **Step 2:** `T` calls `O.wait()` тЖТ **releases the lock** of `O` and parks itself in the wait-set.
- **Step 3:** Another thread can now acquire lock `O` and perform work.
- **Step 4:** That thread calls `O.notify()` or `O.notifyAll()` to wake waiting threads.
- **Step 5:** Awakened thread `T` re-acquires the lock (after the notifier exits the synchronized block) and resumes.

## 2.3 Comparison Matrix тАФ Suspend vs. Wait

| Feature | `Thread.suspend()` (Deprecated) | `Object.wait()` (Modern) |
|---|---|---|
| **Lock Release on Pause** | **No тАФ Lock Retained** | **Yes тАФ Lock Released** |
| **Deadlock Risk** | **High** | Low (depends on logic) |
| **Release Trigger** | External `resume()` call | `notify()` / `notifyAll()` from another thread |
| **Method Type** | `final` instance method | `final` instance method of `Object` |
| **Must be called inside `synchronized`** | No | **Yes тАФ mandatory** |
| **Status in Java** | **Deprecated since JDK 1.2** | Fully supported |
| **Used for** | Arbitrary pause | Inter-thread coordination |

## 2.4 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Symbol / Term | Meaning | KTU Significance |
|---|---|---|
| `suspend()` | Pauses a thread | **Deprecated** since JDK 1.2 |
| `resume()` | Resumes a suspended thread | **Deprecated** since JDK 1.2 |
| `wait()` | Releases lock, waits | Used inside `synchronized` block |
| `notify()` | Wakes one waiter | Used inside `synchronized` block |
| `notifyAll()` | Wakes all waiters | Safer than `notify()` |
| `LockSupport.park()` | Modern low-level pause | From `java.util.concurrent.locks` |
| `Thread.State` | Enum: NEW, RUNNABLE, BLOCKED, WAITING, TIMED\_WAITING, TERMINATED | Used in lifecycle diagrams |

> [!NOTE]
> Note: In the comparison table above, the column "Must be called inside `synchronized`" uses the word "Yes тАФ mandatory" to indicate a **Boolean** condition. Avoid using the `|` character in KTU answer sheets when writing tables.

## 2.5 Real-World Utility

- **Legacy Code Maintenance:** Many enterprise systems (Banking, Telecom) have legacy modules using `suspend()`. Java engineers must recognize and refactor this.
- **Producer-Consumer Pipelines:** Modern thread coordination is built entirely on `wait()`/`notify()` or `BlockingQueue`.
- **Concurrent Collections:** Even `ArrayBlockingQueue` internally uses `Condition.await()` / `Condition.signal()` тАФ direct descendants of the wait/notify model.

