# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Demonstration тАФ The Deadlock Behavior of `suspend()`

Consider the following (intentionally flawed) code that causes a deadlock:

```java
class SharedResource {
    synchronized void produce() {
        System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + " producing...");
        try { Thread.sleep(1000); } catch (Exception e) {}
        System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + " produced. Suspending self.");
        Thread.currentThread().suspend();   // Thread suspends BUT HOLDS THE LOCK
    }
}

public class SuspendDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SharedResource res = new SharedResource();
        Thread producer = new Thread(() -> res.produce(), "Producer");
        producer.start();

        try { Thread.sleep(500); } catch (Exception e) {} // let producer start

        Thread consumer = new Thread(() -> {
            System.out.println("Consumer trying to acquire lock...");
            res.produce();  // Will BLOCK forever because producer holds the lock
            System.out.println("Consumer acquired lock.");
        }, "Consumer");
        consumer.start();
    }
}
```

**Output (truncated):**

```
Producer producing...
Consumer trying to acquire lock...
Producer produced. Suspending self.
[PROGRAM HANGS INDEFINITELY тАФ DEADLOCK]
```

### Step-by-Step Analysis

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Step 1:} \quad & \text{Producer thread enters } \texttt{produce()} \text{ and acquires monitor of } \texttt{res}. \\
\text{Step 2:} \quad & \text{Producer calls } \texttt{Thread.currentThread().suspend()}. \\
\text{Step 3:} \quad & \text{JVM marks producer as Suspended. Lock on } \texttt{res} \text{ is retained.} \\
\text{Step 4:} \quad & \text{Consumer thread calls } \texttt{res.produce()} \rightarrow \text{blocks on monitor entry.} \\
\text{Step 5:} \quad & \text{No one calls } \texttt{producer.resume()} \rightarrow \text{deadlock occurs.}
\end{aligned}
$$

## 3.2 Refactored Version тАФ Using `wait()` / `notify()`

```java
class SharedResource {
    private boolean ready = false;

    synchronized void produce() throws InterruptedException {
        while (ready) {
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + " waiting...");
            wait();  // Releases lock, parks thread
        }
        System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + " producing.");
        Thread.sleep(500);
        ready = true;
        notifyAll();  // Wakes up waiters
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Comparison

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Old Logic:} \quad & \texttt{suspend()} \Rightarrow \text{Lock Retained} \Rightarrow \text{Deadlock} \\
\text{New Logic:} \quad & \texttt{wait()} \Rightarrow \text{Lock Released} \Rightarrow \text{No Deadlock} \Rightarrow \texttt{notifyAll()} \Rightarrow \text{Resume}
\end{aligned}
$$

## 3.3 Analytical Matrix тАФ When to Use What

| Scenario | Use `wait()` / `notify()` | Use `Lock` + `Condition` | Use `suspend()` |
|---|---|---|---|
| Simple single-monitor coordination | **Yes** | Possible | **No** |
| Need to use `java.util.concurrent` | No | **Yes** | **No** |
| Legacy code refactoring | Replacement of suspend | Replacement of suspend | **Only for understanding** |
| Multiple condition predicates | Not natural | **Yes** | **No** |

