## 2.2 High-Yield Methods Cheat Sheet

The table below summarizes the **must-know methods** for KTU exams. These are guaranteed to appear in some form.

| Method (on Component) | Purpose | Example Use |
|------------------------|---------|-------------|
| `setSize(int w, int h)` | Sets width and height in pixels. | `b.setSize(100, 30);` |
| `setLocation(int x, int y)` | Sets position relative to parent's top-left. | `b.setLocation(50, 100);` |
| `setBounds(int x, int y, int w, int h)` | Combined setLocation + setSize. | `b.setBounds(50, 100, 100, 30);` |
| `setBackground(Color c)` | Sets background color. | `b.setBackground(Color.RED);` |
| `setForeground(Color c)` | Sets foreground (text) color. | `lbl.setForeground(Color.BLUE);` |
| `setFont(Font f)` | Sets the font of the component. | `lbl.setFont(new Font("Arial", Font.BOLD, 14));` |
| `setEnabled(boolean)` | Enables or disables interaction. | `b.setEnabled(false);` |
| `setVisible(boolean)` | Shows or hides the component. | `frame.setVisible(true);` |
| `repaint()` | Requests the component to be redrawn. | `panel.repaint();` |
| `addMouseListener(MouseListener)` | Registers a mouse event handler. | `b.addMouseListener(this);` |
| `addKeyListener(KeyListener)` | Registers a keyboard event handler. | `tf.addKeyListener(this);` |

| Method (on Container) | Purpose | Example Use |
|------------------------|---------|-------------|
| `add(Component c)` | Appends a component to the container. | `frame.add(btn);` |
| `add(Component c, Object constraints)` | Adds with layout-specific constraints. | `add(btn, BorderLayout.NORTH);` |
| `remove(Component c)` | Removes a child component. | `frame.remove(btn);` |
| `removeAll()` | Removes every child component. | `panel.removeAll();` |
| `setLayout(LayoutManager mgr)` | Assigns a layout strategy. | `frame.setLayout(new FlowLayout());` |
| `getLayout()` | Returns the current layout manager. | `LayoutManager lm = frame.getLayout();` |
| `getComponentCount()` | Returns number of child components. | `int n = frame.getComponentCount();` |
| `validate()` | Recalculates layout after child changes. | `frame.validate();` |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Exam Trap:** After dynamically adding/removing components at runtime, you **must** call `validate()` (or `revalidate()`) on the container, otherwise the layout will not refresh properly. Examiners love to test this subtlety.

---

## 2.3 Layout Managers Reference (Built-in)

Every `Container` is governed by a **Layout Manager** that dictates *how* child components are positioned. Java provides 5 built-in managers:

| Layout Manager | Arrangement Strategy | Key Constructor | When to Use |
|----------------|----------------------|-----------------|-------------|
| `FlowLayout` | Left-to-right, wraps to next line. Default for `Panel`. | `new FlowLayout()` or `new FlowLayout(int align)` | Rows of buttons (e.g., OK / Cancel). |
| `BorderLayout` | 5 zones: NORTH, SOUTH, EAST, WEST, CENTER. Default for `Frame`. | `new BorderLayout()` or `new BorderLayout(int hgap, int vgap)` | Main app windows with distinct regions. |
| `GridLayout` | Uniform grid of rows ├Ч columns. | `new GridLayout(int rows, int cols)` | Calculator-style keypads. |
| `CardLayout` | Stack of cards, only one visible at a time. | `new CardLayout()` | Tab-like wizards. |
| `GridBagLayout` | Most flexible тАФ fine-grained grid with constraints. | `new GridBagLayout()` | Complex, professional forms. |

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistake:** If you call `frame.setLayout(null)`, you are using **absolute positioning** (no layout manager). In that case, you **must** call `setBounds(x, y, w, h)` on every child, or they will collapse to `(0,0,0,0)` and disappear. AWT does **not** auto-size with `null` layout.

---

## 2.4 Engineering Real-World Utility

Components and Containers form the **backbone of every Java desktop GUI** тАФ from internal banking tools and inventory dashboards to legacy industrial SCADA interfaces. In modern Java, `Swing` (built on AWT) and `JavaFX` inherit AWT's component-container model, so mastering this topic directly enables you to learn any modern Java UI toolkit rapidly. In **embedded and IoT engineering**, lightweight AWT-style hierarchies are also used for kiosk displays and operator panels.

---

## 2.5 Analytical Matrix: Component vs. Container

| Aspect | Component | Container |
|--------|-----------|-----------|
| **Inheritance** | Direct subclass of `Object` (via `Component`). | Subclass of `Component` (via `Container`). |
| **Purpose** | Visual element user sees/interacts with. | Organizes and holds other components. |
| **Can hold children?** | тЭМ No. | тЬЕ Yes тАФ `add()`, `remove()`. |
| **Has layout manager?** | тЭМ No. | тЬЕ Yes тАФ `setLayout()`. |
| **Examples** | `Button`, `Label`, `TextField`, `Checkbox`. | `Frame`, `Panel`, `Dialog`, `Applet`. |
| **Top-level?** | N/A. | Some are top-level (`Frame`, `Dialog`), some are not (`Panel`). |
| **Instantiable directly?** | No тАФ it's abstract. | No тАФ it's abstract. |
