## 3.2 Derivation: A Multi-Component Form Using `BorderLayout`

**Goal:** Build a small login form with a title (NORTH), an input area (CENTER), and a button bar (SOUTH).

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class LoginFrame extends Frame implements ActionListener {

    TextField usernameField;
    Button submitBtn, clearBtn;

    LoginFrame() {
        // Use BorderLayout (already default for Frame, but stated explicitly)
        setLayout(new BorderLayout(10, 10));

        // ---- NORTH: title label ----
        Label title = new Label("   KTU Login Portal   ", Label.CENTER);
        title.setFont(new Font("Serif", Font.BOLD, 20));
        title.setBackground(Color.CYAN);
        add(title, BorderLayout.NORTH);

        // ---- CENTER: a panel holding label + textfield ----
        Panel centerPanel = new Panel(new GridLayout(2, 2, 5, 5));
        centerPanel.add(new Label("Username:"));
        usernameField = new TextField(20);
        centerPanel.add(usernameField);
        centerPanel.add(new Label("Password:"));
        centerPanel.add(new TextField(20));
        add(centerPanel, BorderLayout.CENTER);

        // ---- SOUTH: a panel with two buttons ----
        Panel southPanel = new Panel(new FlowLayout());
        submitBtn = new Button("Submit");
        clearBtn  = new Button("Clear");
        submitBtn.addActionListener(this);
        clearBtn.addActionListener(this);
        southPanel.add(submitBtn);
        southPanel.add(clearBtn);
        add(southPanel, BorderLayout.SOUTH);

        // Frame config
        setTitle("Login");
        setSize(350, 200);
        setVisible(true);

        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) { System.exit(0); }
        });
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        if (e.getSource() == clearBtn) {
            usernameField.setText("");
        } else if (e.getSource() == submitBtn) {
            System.out.println("Submitted: " + usernameField.getText());
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new LoginFrame();
    }
}
```

### Logical Flow Analysis

- The **outer Frame** uses `BorderLayout` with 10px gaps тЖТ it has 3 meaningful slots filled.
- The **NORTH slot** holds a single `Label` тАФ `BorderLayout` stretches it to the full width.
- The **CENTER slot** holds a `Panel` (which is itself a Container). This is the *nesting* principle: containers-inside-containers. The inner `Panel` uses `GridLayout(2,2)` to neatly arrange 2 labels and 2 text fields.
- The **SOUTH slot** holds another `Panel` with `FlowLayout` to place 2 buttons side-by-side.
- `implements ActionListener` lets a single object handle events from multiple buttons. `e.getSource()` identifies which button fired.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why nest Panels?** Because `BorderLayout` only allows **one component per region**. If you need multiple components in one region (like 2 buttons in the SOUTH), you must place a *Panel* there, and put the components *inside* the Panel.

---

## 3.3 Analytical Matrix: Common Layout Manager Behavior

| Container | Default Layout | Behavior with $n$ Components | Typical Use Case |
|-----------|----------------|------------------------------|------------------|
| `Frame` | `BorderLayout` | First goes CENTER, then N/S/E/W in add-order. | Main app window. |
| `Panel` | `FlowLayout` | All placed left-to-right, wrapping. | Button rows, input groups. |
| `Applet` | `FlowLayout` | Same as Panel. | Legacy web applets. |
| `Dialog` | `BorderLayout` | Same as Frame. | Message popups. |
| `ScrollPane` | Internal (single child) | One component, scrollable. | Displaying large images/text. |

