## 3.4 Step-by-Step Construction: Dynamic Component Addition

A common exam question is: *"Add a new Button to a Panel when a menu item is clicked."*

### Logic Derivation

1. Store a reference to the target container as a field.
2. Inside the event handler, instantiate a new `Component` (e.g., `new Button("New " + count)`).
3. Call `container.add(newComponent)`.
4. Call `container.validate()` to force the layout manager to reflow.
5. Optionally call `container.repaint()` to redraw.

### Code Skeleton

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class DynamicPanelDemo extends Frame implements ActionListener {
    Panel centerPanel;
    int count = 0;

    DynamicPanelDemo() {
        setLayout(new BorderLayout());
        centerPanel = new Panel(new FlowLayout());
        add(centerPanel, BorderLayout.CENTER);

        Button addBtn = new Button("Add Button");
        addBtn.addActionListener(this);
        add(addBtn, BorderLayout.SOUTH);

        setSize(300, 200);
        setVisible(true);

        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) { System.exit(0); }
        });
    }

    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        count++;
        centerPanel.add(new Button("Button " + count));
        centerPanel.validate();   // <-- critical!
        centerPanel.repaint();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new DynamicPanelDemo();
    }
}
```

> [!WARNING]
> **Forgetting `validate()` is the #1 mistake** in dynamic GUI code. Without it, the new component is *logically* added to the container's internal list but is *not* displayed until the layout is recalculated.
