### **Question A (14 Marks)** `[KTU University Exam тАУ Model Paper 2024]`

#### (a) [7 Marks] Explain the AWT class hierarchy of `Component` and `Container` with a neat diagram. List the direct subclasses of each.

**Model Solution:**

The AWT class hierarchy places `java.awt.Component` directly under `java.lang.Object` and `java.awt.Container` directly under `Component`. Hence, every container *is also* a component, but with the extra ability to hold child components.

**Direct subclasses of `Component` (non-container components):**
- `Button`, `Canvas`, `Checkbox`, `Choice`, `Label`, `List`, `Scrollbar`, `TextArea`, `TextField`

**Direct subclasses of `Container`:**
- `Panel`, `Window`, `ScrollPane`

**Further subclasses:**
- `Panel` тЖТ `Applet`
- `Window` тЖТ `Frame`, `Dialog`
- `Dialog` тЖТ `FileDialog`

```
Object
  тФФтФАтФА Component (abstract)
         тФЬтФАтФА Button
         тФЬтФАтФА Label
         тФЬтФАтФА TextField
         тФЬтФАтФА TextArea
         тФЬтФАтФА Checkbox
         тФЬтФАтФА Choice
         тФЬтФАтФА List
         тФЬтФАтФА Canvas
         тФЬтФАтФА Scrollbar
         тФФтФАтФА Container (abstract)
                тФЬтФАтФА Panel тФАтФА> Applet
                тФЬтФАтФА Window тФАтФА> Frame
                тФВ           тФФтФАтФА> Dialog тФАтФА> FileDialog
                тФФтФАтФА ScrollPane
```

This structure embodies the **Composite Design Pattern**, where containers and components are unified under a common superclass, allowing uniform treatment while preserving the specialized "holding" behavior of containers.

