#### (b) [7 Marks] Write a Java AWT program to create a `Frame` titled **"Student Entry"** with a `Label` "Roll No:" and a `TextField` for input, placed using `BorderLayout`. Handle the window-close event so the program exits when the X button is clicked.

**Model Solution:**

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class StudentEntry extends Frame implements ActionListener {

    TextField rollField;

    StudentEntry() {
        // Set BorderLayout with 10px gaps
        setLayout(new BorderLayout(10, 10));

        // NORTH: title label
        Label title = new Label("   Student Entry Form   ", Label.CENTER);
        title.setFont(new Font("Arial", Font.BOLD, 18));
        add(title, BorderLayout.NORTH);

        // CENTER: a panel containing label + textfield
        Panel inputPanel = new Panel(new FlowLayout());
        inputPanel.add(new Label("Roll No:"));
        rollField = new TextField(15);
        inputPanel.add(rollField);
        add(inputPanel, BorderLayout.CENTER);

        // SOUTH: a submit button
        Button submit = new Button("Submit");
        submit.addActionListener(this);
        add(submit, BorderLayout.SOUTH);

        // Frame config
        setTitle("Student Entry");
        setSize(350, 200);
        setVisible(true);

        // Handle close button
        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
                System.exit(0);
            }
        });
    }

    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        System.out.println("Roll No entered: " + rollField.getText());
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new StudentEntry();
    }
}
```

**Explanation of key steps:**

1. The `Frame` is configured with `BorderLayout(10, 10)` тАФ horizontal and vertical gaps of 10px.
2. The `Label` is added with constraint `BorderLayout.NORTH` тАФ it stretches across the top.
3. A `Panel` (which itself uses `FlowLayout`) is added to the `CENTER` region, holding a `Label` and `TextField` side-by-side. **A `Panel` is required** because `BorderLayout` permits only one component per region.
4. A `Button` is added to the `SOUTH` region.
5. The `WindowAdapter` (an empty-implementation class of the `WindowListener` interface) overrides only `windowClosing` to invoke `System.exit(0)`.
6. `setVisible(true)` triggers the OS-level display of the frame and all its children.

