### **Question B (14 Marks)** `[KTU University Exam тАУ Model Paper 2024]`

#### (a) [7 Marks] Discuss the role of Layout Managers in Java AWT. Compare `FlowLayout`, `BorderLayout`, and `GridLayout` with examples.

**Model Solution:**

A **Layout Manager** is an object that implements the `java.awt.LayoutManager` interface and is responsible for **positioning and sizing** the components inside a container. Rather than the programmer manually placing every pixel, the layout manager applies a strategy to arrange children automatically. This makes GUIs:
- **Portable** across different screen resolutions and OSes.
- **Resizable** тАФ components re-flow when the window is resized.
- **Maintainable** тАФ adding/removing components does not break positioning.

**Comparison Table:**

| Feature | `FlowLayout` | `BorderLayout` | `GridLayout` |
|---------|--------------|----------------|--------------|
| **Default for** | `Panel` | `Frame`, `Dialog` | None (must be set explicitly) |
| **Arrangement** | Left-to-right, top-to-bottom, wraps. | 5 regions: N, S, E, W, CENTER. | Uniform grid of rows ├Ч columns. |
| **Component sizes** | Preferred size. | NORTH/SOUTH full width; EAST/WEST preferred height; CENTER fills remainder. | Equal cell sizes. |
| **Number of components** | Unlimited. | Up to 5 (one per region). | Unlimited (arranged by row-major). |
| **Constructor** | `new FlowLayout()` or `new FlowLayout(int align)` | `new BorderLayout()` or `new BorderLayout(int h, int v)` | `new GridLayout(rows, cols)` |

**Example тАФ `FlowLayout`:**
```java
Panel p = new Panel(new FlowLayout(FlowLayout.LEFT, 5, 5));
p.add(new Button("A")); p.add(new Button("B")); p.add(new Button("C"));
```
Result: Buttons appear left-to-right in a single line, with 5px gaps.

**Example тАФ `BorderLayout`:**
```java
setLayout(new BorderLayout());
add(new Button("Top"),    BorderLayout.NORTH);
add(new Button("Bottom"), BorderLayout.SOUTH);
add(new Button("Left"),   BorderLayout.WEST);
add(new Button("Right"),  BorderLayout.EAST);
add(new Button("Center"), BorderLayout.CENTER);
```
Result: Buttons occupy the five cardinal regions of the frame.

**Example тАФ `GridLayout`:**
```java
setLayout(new GridLayout(2, 2));
add(new Button("1")); add(new Button("2"));
add(new Button("3")); add(new Button("4"));
```
Result: A 2├Ч2 grid of equal-sized buttons (like a phone keypad).

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Valuation Warning:** Students often write "`FlowLayout` is the default for `Frame`" тАФ **this is wrong**. `FlowLayout` is the default for `Panel` (and `Applet`); `BorderLayout` is the default for `Frame` and `Dialog`. Examiners deduct **1 mark** for this swap.

