#### (b) [7 Marks] Explain the AWT component `TextField` with its commonly used constructors and methods. Write a program to create a TextField that displays a greeting when the user presses **Enter**.

**Model Solution:**

`java.awt.TextField` is a single-line editable text component that allows the user to enter or display text. It extends `TextComponent`.

**Common Constructors:**

| Constructor | Purpose |
|-------------|---------|
| `TextField()` | Empty textfield with default width. |
| `TextField(int columns)` | Empty textfield with the specified width in columns. |
| `TextField(String text)` | Pre-filled textfield. |
| `TextField(String text, int columns)` | Pre-filled textfield with specified width. |

**Common Methods (inherited from `TextComponent` and `Component`):**

| Method | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `setText(String s)` | Sets the text content. |
| `getText()` | Returns the current text. |
| `setEditable(boolean)` | Allows/prevents editing. |
| `setEchoChar(char c)` | Masks input (e.g., for passwords). |
| `addActionListener(ActionListener)` | Registers a listener for the **Enter** key. |
| `selectAll()` | Highlights all text. |

**Important:** A `TextField` fires an `ActionEvent` (and thus triggers its `ActionListener`) when the user presses the **Enter** key inside it. This is the key insight for the program below.

**Program:**

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class GreetingApp extends Frame implements ActionListener {

    TextField nameField;
    Label greeting;

    GreetingApp() {
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        add(new Label("Enter your name:"));
        nameField = new TextField(20);
        nameField.addActionListener(this);   // <-- listens for Enter key
        add(nameField);

        greeting = new Label("                                ");
        greeting.setFont(new Font("Arial", Font.PLAIN, 16));
        add(greeting);

        setTitle("Greeting App");
        setSize(350, 150);
        setVisible(true);

        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) { System.exit(0); }
        });
    }

    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        if (e.getSource() == nameField) {
            String name = nameField.getText();
            greeting.setText("Hello, " + name + "!");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new GreetingApp();
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**

1. A `TextField` named `nameField` is registered with an `ActionListener` via `addActionListener(this)`.
2. When the user types a name and presses **Enter**, AWT internally creates an `ActionEvent` and dispatches it to the listener.
3. The `actionPerformed` method calls `nameField.getText()` to retrieve the input and updates the `Label`'s text using `setText()`.
4. This pattern is the foundation of every simple form-based Java AWT application.

