# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Anatomy of the Delegation Event Model (DEM)

The DEM is structured around a **publish-subscribe** architecture. Every GUI component maintains an internal list (called the **listener list**) of registered listener objects. When an event occurs, the source iterates this list and invokes the appropriate callback method on each listener.

### 2.1.1 Step-by-Step Flow of an Event

1. **User Interaction**: The user performs a GUI action (click, type, etc.).
2. **Event Object Creation**: The JVM creates an event object (e.g., `ActionEvent`) and passes it to the source component.
3. **Event Dispatching**: The source's `processEvent()` method is called, which delegates to `processXxxEvent()`.
4. **Listener Notification**: The source iterates through its listener list and calls the corresponding interface method on each listener.
5. **Event Handling Logic**: The listener's overridden method executes, performing the desired action.

---

## 2.2 Classification of Events in `java.awt.event`

Java categorizes events into **Semantic Events** and **Low-Level Events**.

### 2.2.1 Semantic Events (High-Level)

These represent a meaningful user action interpreted by the component.

| Event Class | Triggered When | Listener Interface |
|---|---|---|
| `ActionEvent` | Button click, menu selection, Enter in text field | `ActionListener` |
| `ItemEvent` | Checkbox/Radio button toggle, list selection | `ItemListener` |
| `TextEvent` | Text content changes | `TextListener` |
| `AdjustmentEvent` | Scrollbar movement | `AdjustmentListener` |

### 2.2.2 Low-Level Events

These capture raw input from the user, regardless of component semantics.

| Event Class | Triggered When | Listener Interface |
|---|---|---|
| `MouseEvent` | Click, press, release, enter, exit, move, drag | `MouseListener`, `MouseMotionListener` |
| `KeyEvent` | Key press, release, type | `KeyListener` |
| `FocusEvent` | Component gains/loses focus | `FocusListener` |
| `WindowEvent` | Window open, close, iconify, activate | `WindowListener` |
| `ComponentEvent` | Component shown, hidden, moved, resized | `ComponentListener` |
| `ContainerEvent` | Component added/removed from container | `ContainerListener` |

---

## 2.3 Key Interfaces in `java.awt.event`

### 2.3.1 `ActionListener` тАФ The Most Common Listener

```java
public interface ActionListener extends EventListener {
    void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e);
}
```

Used for: `JButton`, `JMenuItem`, `JTextField` (on Enter), `JComboBox` (on selection confirmation).

### 2.3.2 `MouseListener` тАФ 5 Abstract Methods

```java
public interface MouseListener extends EventListener {
    void mouseClicked(MouseEvent e);
    void mousePressed(MouseEvent e);
    void mouseReleased(MouseEvent e);
    void mouseEntered(MouseEvent e);
    void mouseExited(MouseEvent e);
}
```

### 2.3.3 `KeyListener` тАФ 3 Abstract Methods

```java
public interface KeyListener extends EventListener {
    void keyTyped(KeyEvent e);    // Character typed
    void keyPressed(KeyEvent e);  // Physical key down
    void keyReleased(KeyEvent e); // Physical key up
}
```

### 2.3.4 `WindowListener` тАФ 7 Abstract Methods

```java
public interface WindowListener extends EventListener {
    void windowOpened(WindowEvent e);
    void windowClosing(WindowEvent e);
    void windowClosed(WindowEvent e);
    void windowIconified(WindowEvent e);
    void windowDeiconified(WindowEvent e);
    void windowActivated(WindowEvent e);
    void windowDeactivated(WindowEvent e);
}
```

---

## 2.4 Adapter Classes тАФ Solving the "Empty Method" Problem

> [!NOTE]
> **Problem:** Interfaces like `MouseListener` and `WindowListener` have **many abstract methods**. If you only need to handle one, you are forced to implement *all* of them with empty bodies.

**Solution:** Java provides **Adapter Classes** in `java.awt.event` тАФ empty implementations of listener interfaces. You extend the adapter and override only the methods you need.

| Adapter Class | Implements | Methods Provided |
|---|---|---|
| `MouseAdapter` | `MouseListener`, `MouseMotionListener` | 7 empty methods |
| `KeyAdapter` | `KeyListener` | 3 empty methods |
| `WindowAdapter` | `WindowListener`, `WindowStateListener` | 9 empty methods |
| `FocusAdapter` | `FocusListener` | 2 empty methods |

```java
btn.addMouseListener(new MouseAdapter() {
    @Override
    public void mouseClicked(MouseEvent e) {
        // Only the click logic тАФ no empty method clutter
    }
});
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Anonymous Inner Classes** combined with **Adapters** is the **standard KTU exam pattern** for writing concise event handlers.

---

## 2.5 The Three Ways to Implement Event Listeners

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Exam Favourite тАФ Memorize These Three Patterns:**

### Pattern 1: Separate Class Implementing the Interface
```java
class MyHandler implements ActionListener {
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        // handle event
    }
}
btn.addActionListener(new MyHandler());
```

### Pattern 2: The Same Class Implements the Interface
The class containing `main()` also implements `ActionListener`. Used in `JFrame` extensions.

### Pattern 3: Anonymous Inner Class
```java
btn.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        // handle event
    }
});
```

> **Pattern 3 is the most idiomatic in modern Swing code.**

