# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 The Event Dispatching Chain тАФ Step-by-Step Trace

When the user clicks a `JButton`, the following sequence unfolds at the JVM level:

**Step 1: Native Notification**
The operating system detects a mouse click and notifies the AWT subsystem.

**Step 2: Event Object Construction**
The JVM constructs an `ActionEvent` object containing:
- `source` тЖТ reference to the `JButton` that was clicked
- `id` тЖТ `ActionEvent.ACTION_PERFORMED` (1001)
- `command` тЖТ the button's label (e.g., "Submit")
- `modifiers` тЖТ current modifier keys held

**Step 3: `Component.processEvent()` Invocation**
Each AWT/Swing component inherits `processEvent(AWTEvent e)` from `java.awt.Component`. This method inspects the event ID and dispatches it.

**Step 4: Type-Specific Dispatch**
Inside `processEvent`, a switch-style check (implemented via `Component.processActionEvent()`) routes the call to the appropriate `processXxxEvent()` method.

**Step 5: Listener Notification Loop**
The `processXxxEvent()` method iterates the component's internal listener list and invokes the interface method on each registered listener.

**Step 6: Listener Method Execution**
Your overridden `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)` runs, executing your custom logic.

### The Chain Visualized

$$
\text{User Click} \rightarrow \text{OS Event} \rightarrow \text{ActionEvent object} \rightarrow \text{Component.processEvent()}
$$

$$
\rightarrow \text{Component.processActionEvent()} \rightarrow \text{Listener.actionPerformed()} \rightarrow \text{Custom Logic}
$$

---

## 3.2 Analytical Matrix: Choosing the Right Listener

| Scenario | Recommended Listener | Why |
|---|---|---|
| "OK" button click | `ActionListener` | High-level semantic event |
| Detect Ctrl+Click | `MouseListener` + `getModifiers()` | Low-level mouse event with modifier |
| Detect arrow key press | `KeyListener` + `getKeyCode()` | Low-level key event |
| Confirm "Are you sure?" on close | `WindowListener` | Window-level event |
| Highlight a text field on focus | `FocusListener` | Focus tracking |
| Detect mouse drag drawing | `MouseMotionListener` (use `MouseAdapter`) | Continuous motion events |
| Log when a panel becomes visible | `ComponentListener` (use `ComponentAdapter`) | Component lifecycle |
| React to dropdown change | `ItemListener` | Selection state change |

---

## 3.3 Worked Example: Building a Login Authentication System

Let's derive the event-handling logic for a simple **Login Form** with username, password fields, and a Login button.

### Step 1: Define Fields and Components

```java
JTextField usernameField = new JTextField(15);
JPasswordField passwordField = new JPasswordField(15);
JButton loginButton = new JButton("Login");
JLabel statusLabel = new JLabel(" ");
```

### Step 2: Register the ActionListener

```java
loginButton.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        // Step 3: Extract data from event source
        String user = usernameField.getText();
        String pass = new String(passwordField.getPassword());

        // Step 4: Validate credentials
        if (user.equals("admin") && pass.equals("1234")) {
            statusLabel.setText("Login Successful!");
        } else {
            statusLabel.setText("Invalid credentials.");
        }

        // Step 5: Clear password field for security
        passwordField.setText("");
    }
});
```

### Step 3: Add Window Listener for Clean Exit

```java
frame.addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
    @Override
    public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
        System.exit(0);
    }
});
```

### Step 4: Add Key Listener for Enter Key Submit

```java
passwordField.addKeyListener(new KeyAdapter() {
    @Override
    public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) {
        if (e.getKeyCode() == KeyEvent.VK_ENTER) {
            loginButton.doClick();  // Programmatically triggers the button
        }
    }
});
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Exam Insight:** The combination of `ActionListener` (button), `KeyListener` (Enter key), and `WindowListener` (close) on a single form is a **classic 14-mark question** pattern.

---

## 3.4 The `EventObject` Hierarchy тАФ Class Derivation

All event classes ultimately extend `java.util.EventObject`, which guarantees a `getSource()` method.

$$
\text{java.util.EventObject} \rightarrow \text{java.awt.AWTEvent} \rightarrow \text{ActionEvent}
$$

$$
\text{java.util.EventObject} \rightarrow \text{java.awt.AWTEvent} \rightarrow \text{ComponentEvent} \rightarrow \text{MouseEvent}
$$

$$
\text{java.util.EventObject} \rightarrow \text{java.awt.AWTEvent} \rightarrow \text{ComponentEvent} \rightarrow \text{KeyEvent}
$$

> [!NOTE]
> `AWTEvent` defines the event ID constants (e.g., `ACTION_EVENT_MASK = 1L << 50`). These mask bits are how the dispatcher identifies the event type.

---

## 3.5 Multi-Listener Scenario: One Source, Many Listeners

A single `JButton` can be registered with **multiple** listeners of **different types**:

```java
JButton b = new JButton("Multi");

// Listener 1: ActionListener for clicks
b.addActionListener(e -> System.out.println("Clicked!"));

// Listener 2: MouseListener for hover effects
b.addMouseListener(new MouseAdapter() {
    @Override
    public void mouseEntered(MouseEvent e) {
        b.setBackground(Color.YELLOW);
    }
    @Override
    public void mouseExited(MouseEvent e) {
        b.setBackground(null);
    }
});

// Listener 3: KeyListener for keyboard activation
b.addKeyListener(new KeyAdapter() {
    @Override
    public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) {
        if (e.getKeyCode() == KeyEvent.VK_SPACE) {
            b.doClick();
        }
    }
});
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Order of invocation is not guaranteed** for multiple listeners of the same type on a single source. Do not depend on listener execution order.

