#### Model Solution to Q-A(a):

**The Three Implementation Patterns:**

**Pattern 1: Separate Class Implementing the Listener Interface**

```java
import java.awt.event.*;
import javax.swing.*;

class ClickHandler implements ActionListener {
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(null, "Button Clicked!");
    }
}

public class Demo1 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        JFrame f = new JFrame("Pattern 1");
        JButton b = new JButton("Click");
        b.addActionListener(new ClickHandler());
        f.add(b); f.setSize(200,100); f.setVisible(true);
    }
}
```

**Advantages:** Reusable across multiple components. Clean separation of concerns.

**Pattern 2: The Same Class Implements the Interface**

```java
public class Demo2 extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JButton b;
    Demo2() {
        b = new JButton("Click");
        b.addActionListener(this);  // 'this' refers to the JFrame
        add(b); setSize(200,100);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        b.setText("Clicked!");
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) { new Demo2(); }
}
```

**Advantages:** Compact. Suitable when one class owns both the GUI and the logic.

**Pattern 3: Anonymous Inner Class**

```java
public class Demo3 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        JFrame f = new JFrame("Pattern 3");
        JButton b = new JButton("Click");
        b.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
                JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(null, "Clicked!");
            }
        });
        f.add(b); f.setSize(200,100); f.setVisible(true);
    }
}
```

**Advantages:** Most compact; used when handler is needed only once.

**Pattern 4 (Bonus): Lambda Expression (Java 8+)**

```java
b.addActionListener(e -> JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(null, "Clicked!"));
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Marks Distribution:** 2 marks for each of the 3 patterns (1 for explanation + 1 for code) + 1 mark for comparison.

