#### Model Solution to Q-B(b):

**`WindowListener` Interface:**
- Contains **7 abstract methods** for window-level events: `windowOpened`, `windowClosing`, `windowClosed`, `windowIconified`, `windowDeiconified`, `windowActivated`, `windowDeactivated`.

**`WindowAdapter` Class:**
- Provides empty implementations of all 7 methods.
- Used to override only `windowClosing` (or whichever is needed), avoiding boilerplate.

**Program:**

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class ConfirmCloseDemo extends JFrame {
    public ConfirmCloseDemo() {
        setTitle("Confirm Close Demo");
        setSize(300, 200);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(DO_NOTHING_ON_CLOSE);  // Disable default close

        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            @Override
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
                int choice = JOptionPane.showConfirmDialog(
                    ConfirmCloseDemo.this,
                    "Are you sure you want to exit?",
                    "Confirm Exit",
                    JOptionPane.YES_NO_OPTION
                );
                if (choice == JOptionPane.YES_OPTION) {
                    System.exit(0);
                }
            }
        });

        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new ConfirmCloseDemo();
    }
}
```

**Key Points:**
- `setDefaultCloseOperation(DO_NOTHING_ON_CLOSE)` prevents automatic close, allowing the listener to take control.
- `WindowAdapter` is used to avoid implementing all 7 methods.
- `JOptionPane.showConfirmDialog` returns an integer constant (`YES_OPTION`, `NO_OPTION`, `CANCEL_OPTION`).

> [!NOTE]
> **Marks Distribution:** Interface explanation: 1.5 marks | Adapter explanation: 1.5 marks | Program: 3 marks | Output explanation: 1 mark.

