#### **Question A (14 Marks)**

**[KTU University Exam тАУ June 2024, Model]**
**(a)** Explain the different methods available in Java for deleting files and directories. Compare `File.delete()` and `Files.delete()` with suitable examples. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program to delete a non-empty directory named `"ProjectBackup"` along with all its sub-files and sub-directories. Use the `java.io.File` class with recursion. **(7 marks)**

### Model Solution:

**(a) Explanation (7 marks):**

Java provides three primary methods for deletion:

1. **`java.io.File.delete()`** тАФ A boolean method that returns `true` if the file/empty-directory was successfully deleted, otherwise `false`. It is a *legacy* method (JDK 1.0) and does not throw exceptions. It **cannot** delete non-empty directories.

2. **`java.nio.file.Files.delete(Path)`** тАФ A modern method (JDK 7) that returns `void` and throws `IOException` (or its subclasses like `NoSuchFileException`, `DirectoryNotEmptyException`) when deletion fails. It enforces explicit error handling via try-catch.

3. **`java.nio.file.Files.deleteIfExists(Path)`** тАФ Returns `boolean`. Returns `true` if the file existed and was deleted, `false` if the file did not exist. It is **idempotent** and only throws an exception for *unrecoverable* errors like attempting to delete a non-empty directory.

**Example Comparison:**

```java
// Approach 1: Legacy
File f = new File("data.txt");
if (f.delete()) {
    System.out.println("Deleted.");
} else {
    System.out.println("Failed (no exception).");
}

// Approach 2: Modern
Path p = Paths.get("data.txt");
try {
    Files.delete(p);
    System.out.println("Deleted.");
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.out.println("Failed: " + e.getMessage());
}
```

**(b) Java Program (7 marks):**

```java
import java.io.File;

public class DeleteDirectory {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        File dir = new File("ProjectBackup");
        deleteDir(dir);
    }

    public static void deleteDir(File file) {
        if (file == null || !file.exists()) return;

        if (file.isDirectory()) {
            File[] entries = file.listFiles();
            if (entries != null) {
                for (File entry : entries) {
                    deleteDir(entry);  // Recursive call
                }
            }
        }
        file.delete();
        System.out.println("Deleted: " + file.getAbsolutePath());
    }
}
```

**Explanation:** The method `deleteDir()` performs a *depth-first traversal* of the directory tree. It first checks if the target is a directory; if so, it lists all children and recursively deletes them. Finally, it deletes the (now-empty) parent directory itself.

