#### **Question B (14 Marks) тАФ Alternative Choice**

**[KTU University Exam тАУ Dec 2023, Model]**
**(a)** What is the role of `deleteOnExit()`? Explain with a suitable Java program that creates a temporary file, writes data to it, and then ensures it is deleted when the JVM exits. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program using the **NIO.2** API (`java.nio.file.Files` and `java.nio.file.Paths`) to demonstrate:
   - (i) Deletion of an existing file using `Files.delete()`.
   - (ii) Idempotent deletion using `Files.deleteIfExists()`.
   - **(iii)** Proper exception handling for the case where the file does not exist. **(7 marks)**

### Model Solution:

**(a) `deleteOnExit()` Explanation (7 marks):**

`deleteOnExit()` is a method in the `java.io.File` class that registers the file for deletion when the JVM terminates. It is useful for **temporary file cleanup**.

```java
import java.io.*;

public class TempFileCleanup {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        File temp = File.createTempFile("temp_data_", ".tmp");
        temp.deleteOnExit();

        // Write data to the file
        try (FileWriter fw = new FileWriter(temp)) {
            fw.write("Temporary processing data\n");
        }

        System.out.println("Temp file created: " + temp.getAbsolutePath());
        System.out.println("File will be deleted on JVM exit.");
    }
}
```

**(b) NIO.2 Deletion Program (7 marks):**

```java
import java.nio.file.*;
import java.io.IOException;

public class NioDeleteDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Path filePath = Paths.get("report.pdf");

        // (i) Files.delete() - throws exception if file does not exist
        try {
            Files.delete(filePath);
            System.out.println("(i) File deleted successfully.");
        } catch (NoSuchFileException e) {
            System.out.println("(i) File not found: " + e.getMessage());
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("(i) I/O Error: " + e.getMessage());
        }

        // (ii) Files.deleteIfExists() - returns false if file did not exist
        try {
            boolean result = Files.deleteIfExists(filePath);
            if (result) {
                System.out.println("(ii) File existed and was deleted.");
            } else {
                System.out.println("(ii) File did not exist. No action needed.");
            }
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("(ii) Unrecoverable I/O error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**
- (i) `Files.delete()` is used when the file **must** exist. It throws `NoSuchFileException` if the file is absent.
- (ii) `Files.deleteIfExists()` is **idempotent** тАФ it returns `false` instead of throwing an exception when the file does not exist. It is preferred for **cleanup tasks** where the existence of the file is uncertain.

