### 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- ЁЯУМ **`File.delete()`** is a *boolean* method that silently fails (returns `false`) тАФ it does not throw exceptions. Use it for quick, non-critical deletions.
- ЁЯУМ **`Files.delete()`** is the *modern, exception-based* alternative. It throws `IOException` for any failure. Mandatory try-catch block required.
- ЁЯУМ **`Files.deleteIfExists()`** is the *idempotent* version. It returns `false` instead of throwing an exception if the file does not exist тАФ ideal for cleanup tasks.
- ЁЯУМ **`deleteOnExit()`** does **NOT** delete immediately. It registers the file for deletion upon **JVM shutdown**. Perfect for temp files.
- ЁЯУМ **Non-empty directories CANNOT be deleted** by any of the above methods directly. Recursive deletion (using `listFiles()` or `Files.walk()`) is required.
- ЁЯУМ The deletion is **permanent** тАФ files do NOT go to the Recycle Bin/Trash when deleted via Java.
- ЁЯУМ The package for legacy deletion is **`java.io.File`**; the package for modern deletion is **`java.nio.file.Files`**.
- ЁЯУМ **JDK 7+** introduced the NIO.2 API, which is the **recommended approach** for production-grade Java code.
- ЁЯУМ The `Path` interface (from NIO.2) is preferred over the older `File` class for representing file paths in modern Java.
- ЁЯУМ **Interview Favorite:** Recursive directory deletion using `java.io.File` is one of the most frequently asked Java coding questions in KTU Module 4 examinations.

